WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.720
[Amit Varma]: Every time you say something you should be amazed. It's a miracle.

00:00:09.720 --> 00:00:13.400
[Amit Varma]: No, I'm not remarking on the quality of your words. I'm not even mocking you in

00:00:13.400 --> 00:00:17.360
[Amit Varma]: some passive-aggressive way. I'm just pointing out that the fact that we can

00:00:17.360 --> 00:00:21.600
[Amit Varma]: speak to each other, that we have language is so remarkable. Part of the

00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:25.320
[Amit Varma]: wonder of this is what our brains can achieve in terms of learning how to

00:00:25.320 --> 00:00:29.880
[Amit Varma]: communicate in this manner. And part of this awe I feel is because of language

00:00:29.880 --> 00:00:34.320
[Amit Varma]: itself. Our languages were not formed out of nothing in a language lab somewhere.

00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:39.520
[Amit Varma]: They were not designed by committee. Instead they arose over centuries, formed

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:44.480
[Amit Varma]: by millions of interactions, shaped by other languages and cultures that are no

00:00:44.480 --> 00:00:49.200
[Amit Varma]: more. Every time we say something, no matter what it is that we say, we are in

00:00:49.200 --> 00:00:53.960
[Amit Varma]: a sense expressing all of human history before us. From the first migrants out of

00:00:53.960 --> 00:00:58.680
[Amit Varma]: Africa to the last thought that you had. Our very words are shaped by the inner

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:02.760
[Amit Varma]: lives of the dead and the undead, by the past and the present, by the seen and the unseen.

00:01:02.760 --> 00:01:10.320
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on

00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:14.720
[Unknown]: economics, politics and behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit

00:01:14.720 --> 00:01:17.120
[Amit Varma]: Varma.

00:01:18.480 --> 00:01:22.640
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen. My guest today is Peggy Mohan, linguist,

00:01:22.640 --> 00:01:26.960
[Amit Varma]: music teacher and author of a remarkable book called Wanderer's King's Merchants,

00:01:26.960 --> 00:01:30.840
[Amit Varma]: the story of India through its languages. This book was an eye-opener for me in

00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:36.200
[Amit Varma]: revealing how language evolves and also of how India evolved through the story

00:01:36.200 --> 00:01:39.760
[Amit Varma]: of its languages. We've heard simple narratives about Indian language before,

00:01:39.760 --> 00:01:44.160
[Amit Varma]: how Sanskrit is part of a larger family of Indo-Aryan languages, sharing an

00:01:44.160 --> 00:01:47.920
[Amit Varma]: ancestor called Proto-Indo-European with Latin and Greek. I was taught in school

00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:51.760
[Amit Varma]: that a bunch of Indian languages like Hindi, Marathi and Bengali are derived

00:01:51.760 --> 00:01:55.560
[Amit Varma]: from Sanskrit, while the South Indian languages are in a separate language

00:01:55.560 --> 00:01:59.600
[Amit Varma]: family. Well, the truth is far more nuanced and our languages are even more

00:01:59.600 --> 00:02:03.880
[Amit Varma]: of a khichdi than you'd imagine. For example, Sanskrit has a bunch of sounds

00:02:03.880 --> 00:02:09.120
[Amit Varma]: called retroflex sounds, the T and D as opposed to the T and D, which are not

00:02:09.120 --> 00:02:14.200
[Amit Varma]: there in any of the other Indo-Aryan languages. Retroflex sounds are unique to

00:02:14.200 --> 00:02:18.880
[Amit Varma]: South Asia. So what happened here? What was the landscape of languages here when

00:02:18.880 --> 00:02:22.640
[Amit Varma]: the Aryans came to India? How does Sanskrit evolve within that landscape?

00:02:22.640 --> 00:02:26.240
[Amit Varma]: Why is a language like Marathi so similar to some of the Dravidian

00:02:26.240 --> 00:02:30.280
[Amit Varma]: languages? Is there a clue in the evolution of more recent languages? For

00:02:30.280 --> 00:02:34.480
[Amit Varma]: example, Peggy writes in a book about how new languages evolved in the Caribbean

00:02:34.480 --> 00:02:38.480
[Amit Varma]: due to the slave trade. Slaves were brought to the Caribbean from West

00:02:38.480 --> 00:02:42.360
[Amit Varma]: Africa. They formed a jugaru kind of language, borrowing nouns from their

00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:47.040
[Amit Varma]: masters, called pigeon languages. And then the next generation gave these pigeon

00:02:47.040 --> 00:02:50.960
[Amit Varma]: languages a structure, an operating system as it were, which had more in

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:55.040
[Amit Varma]: common with West African languages than with the French or English or Spanish

00:02:55.040 --> 00:02:59.500
[Amit Varma]: from which they borrowed nouns. These languages were called Creoles. In a

00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:03.600
[Amit Varma]: similar way, Indian languages often have an external addressing of a particular

00:03:03.600 --> 00:03:08.000
[Amit Varma]: type, but an underlying operating system from somewhere else. How much can we

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.240
[Amit Varma]: understand of this now? How much can we tell about our past from the way our

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:16.340
[Amit Varma]: language is in the present time? What deeper truths about our society and

00:03:16.340 --> 00:03:21.640
[Amit Varma]: culture can language reveal? Peggy's book is a fundamental book if you want to

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:25.560
[Amit Varma]: begin exploring these subjects and I love my conversation with her. Before we

00:03:25.560 --> 00:03:28.480
[Amit Varma]: get there though, let's take a quick commercial break.

