[Amit Varma]: you, glad to be here. I loved reading your book and I was

00:05:00.600 --> 00:05:05.200
[Amit Varma]: especially struck by something in the first chapter where you talk about a

00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:08.920
[Amit Varma]: tiramisu bear. So I'm just going to read that little bit out because I love that

00:05:08.920 --> 00:05:12.960
[Amit Varma]: passage where you say, quote, travelers to the Canadian Arctic have been coming

00:05:12.960 --> 00:05:16.400
[Amit Varma]: back with tales of a new kind of bear in the wild that one could almost call a

00:05:16.400 --> 00:05:20.640
[Amit Varma]: tiramisu bear. It has a layered look like the Italian desert with cream colored

00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:25.360
[Amit Varma]: fur on top and coffee brown paws. Its snout is slender like a polar bear's but

00:05:25.360 --> 00:05:29.120
[Amit Varma]: it has a broad and muscular shoulders of a grizzly. Its feet are something in

00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:32.880
[Amit Varma]: between the furry soles of a polar bear which give good traction on snow and ice

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:36.800
[Amit Varma]: and the planar pads of a grizzly which can withstand the friction of walking on

00:05:36.800 --> 00:05:41.080
[Amit Varma]: barren ground. Stop quote. Now this has many resonances through your book with

00:05:41.080 --> 00:05:44.600
[Amit Varma]: you know different subjects like migration, conquest, language, all of that.

00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:48.960
[Amit Varma]: But what I was particularly intrigued by is when you say that you are a tiramisu

00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:53.480
[Amit Varma]: bear. So let's start by talking about the personal. Tell me a bit about your

00:05:53.480 --> 00:05:58.360
[Amit Varma]: childhood and why are you a tiramisu bear? Well, it's an interesting thought

00:05:58.360 --> 00:06:03.120
[Guest]: because when I start with a Canadian polar bear and the idea of a grizzly

00:06:03.120 --> 00:06:09.240
[Guest]: bear it's almost humorous metaphor of my parents because my mom was from a place

00:06:09.240 --> 00:06:15.280
[Guest]: in Canada where you could possibly conceivably find a polar bear and it was

00:06:15.280 --> 00:06:21.160
[Guest]: an island off the coast of Canada, Newfoundland, and she went as a student

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:27.280
[Guest]: to Canada and that's where my father who was Indian from the Caribbean met her

00:06:27.280 --> 00:06:36.080
[Guest]: and like migrants in early days he was a student planning to go back home. He

00:06:36.080 --> 00:06:40.680
[Guest]: didn't see anything strange about falling in love with her and marrying

00:06:40.680 --> 00:06:47.840
[Guest]: her because the first migrants generally do only find women from the local

00:06:47.840 --> 00:06:55.680
[Guest]: community and I think in both of them were so averse to anything that could be

00:06:55.680 --> 00:07:00.600
[Guest]: considered racist that they wouldn't hesitate for a moment to think that they

00:07:00.600 --> 00:07:06.520
[Guest]: should get married and then my mom went back with him to the Caribbean and as I

00:07:06.520 --> 00:07:13.040
[Guest]: said in the book never ever saw snow again. So in a funny way even my story

00:07:13.040 --> 00:07:18.120
[Guest]: repeats because I've left the Caribbean and gone to India and here's my daughter

00:07:18.120 --> 00:07:25.400
[Guest]: who's with me who's left India and gone to California so it's like we are all

00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:35.240
[Guest]: migrants in my family and tiramisu bear gives a sense of a very predictable kind

00:07:35.240 --> 00:07:44.000
[Guest]: of mixing. So the mixing in languages as with bears always has the male as the

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:50.320
[Guest]: migrant, the female as the one encountered there, and when you look at

00:07:50.320 --> 00:07:56.400
[Guest]: the languages you find the men are sperm donors of vocabulary not very hands-on

00:07:56.400 --> 00:08:03.240
[Guest]: parents and the women are the ones who incubate and raise the offspring and

00:08:03.240 --> 00:08:08.840
[Guest]: perhaps even see the words all change from what they taught the child in the

00:08:08.840 --> 00:08:15.880
[Guest]: early years. So you have these kinds of languages where if you're not looking

00:08:15.880 --> 00:08:20.800
[Guest]: for it you will miss it but the entire grammatical structure and a lot of the

00:08:20.800 --> 00:08:26.160
[Guest]: sounds are there from the woman because they raise the children until about the

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:34.360
[Guest]: age of five after which men might say I want the boys, the boys are us, the girls

00:08:34.360 --> 00:08:41.440
[Guest]: are not. So if you look at the languages you'll find this pattern in so many

00:08:41.440 --> 00:08:46.360
[Guest]: parts of the world not just India, India is just the latest one I found where you

00:08:46.360 --> 00:08:53.800
[Guest]: find a huge grammatical infrastructure we could say operating system which is

00:08:53.800 --> 00:08:59.320
[Guest]: installed where words can shift and the words tend to come from whoever's in

00:08:59.320 --> 00:09:07.200
[Guest]: power who initiated the contact who well who created the need for a hybrid to

00:09:07.200 --> 00:09:11.760
[Guest]: come into existence at all. So okay on the one hand yes I'm talking about

00:09:11.760 --> 00:09:17.160
[Guest]: myself, I'm talking about migrants, I'm talking about languages because when you

00:09:17.160 --> 00:09:22.240
[Guest]: look at languages you can almost forensically say this is what has to

00:09:22.240 --> 00:09:27.280
[Guest]: have happened because I'm seeing the grammar from one place which seems very

00:09:27.280 --> 00:09:33.720
[Guest]: local and I'm seeing the words from another place. So you have a tendency to

00:09:33.720 --> 00:09:41.120
[Guest]: say that I can completely reconstruct the story of how the contact took place.

00:09:41.120 --> 00:09:45.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah that's that's fascinating and there are you know in your book you even talk

00:09:45.320 --> 00:09:49.160
[Amit Varma]: about this tribe in Africa where you know the men speak one language and the

00:09:49.160 --> 00:09:55.360
[Amit Varma]: women speak another language entirely. That's in the Caribbean and in fact I

00:09:55.360 --> 00:10:00.040
[Guest]: had to study that language it was a very strange experience because and I made

00:10:00.040 --> 00:10:04.080
[Guest]: friends with the person who was teaching it but it's something that happened in

00:10:04.080 --> 00:10:11.600
[Guest]: in the island of St. Vincent back in oh the year 1200 that's before Columbus. So

00:10:11.600 --> 00:10:15.720
[Guest]: and this apparently it happened very often because you have things like men

00:10:15.720 --> 00:10:21.280
[Guest]: or shall I say marauders going from island to island doing away with the men

00:10:21.280 --> 00:10:27.960
[Guest]: even a book I'm reading now about the conquests of Alexander they talk of

00:10:27.960 --> 00:10:33.480
[Guest]: things like slaughtering all the men taking all the women. So you have these

00:10:33.480 --> 00:10:39.040
[Guest]: kinds of hybrid situations so this is actually a Carib language. Carib and

00:10:39.040 --> 00:10:45.760
[Guest]: Arawak from the Caribbean yeah. Fascinating let's you know all of these

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:49.720
[Amit Varma]: seems are the things that I want to explore in great detail both migration

00:10:49.720 --> 00:10:53.960
[Amit Varma]: how languages come into being all of that but let's kind of go back to your

00:10:53.960 --> 00:10:57.260
[Amit Varma]: personal journey so you know you're you're kind of growing up in the

00:10:57.260 --> 00:11:01.480
[Amit Varma]: Caribbean as a kid what are you interested in as a kid what are you

00:11:01.480 --> 00:11:05.360
[Amit Varma]: reading what are you doing like later on of course you go to study linguistics

00:11:05.360 --> 00:11:09.800
[Amit Varma]: but how does that interest develop you you're also a teacher of music are you a

00:11:09.800 --> 00:11:12.920
[Amit Varma]: musical kid a lot of people will of course know you through your books and

00:11:12.920 --> 00:11:16.940
[Amit Varma]: your work and all of that but give me a sense of the person beyond that you know

00:11:16.940 --> 00:11:23.120
[Guest]: your early phase as it were. Okay let's see if I can reconstruct that too. I grew

00:11:23.120 --> 00:11:29.160
[Guest]: up in what you would call a joint Indian family in the countryside in Trinidad my

00:11:29.160 --> 00:11:34.360
[Guest]: great-grandfather was alive my grandmother and some of her younger

00:11:34.360 --> 00:11:41.120
[Guest]: siblings and so and my another generation it was just a huge amount of

00:11:41.120 --> 00:11:48.140
[Guest]: people and my mother who was the youngest daughter-in-law and who'd come

00:11:48.140 --> 00:11:53.580
[Guest]: from abroad and everyone spoke Creole English which is somewhat similar to

00:11:53.580 --> 00:12:02.620
[Guest]: Jamaican English and I would hear whiffs of Hindi and of course Bhojpuri now my

00:12:02.620 --> 00:12:07.300
[Guest]: grandmother great-grandfather all these older people were educated they'd

00:12:07.300 --> 00:12:11.700
[Guest]: studied Hindi so they've made it a point that they want to speak Hindi they

00:12:11.700 --> 00:12:15.440
[Guest]: didn't want me to learn it because there was a very strong feeling that that was

00:12:15.440 --> 00:12:21.040
[Guest]: something we were leaving behind the whole identity of having come as

00:12:21.040 --> 00:12:28.860
[Guest]: migrants from India okay that too we were migrants from India in between 1849

00:12:28.860 --> 00:12:35.840
[Guest]: and 1919 quite a lot of Indians mainly from eastern UP a small number from

00:12:35.840 --> 00:12:41.380
[Guest]: western Bihar a small number from the south went as bonded labor to the

00:12:41.380 --> 00:12:48.220
[Guest]: plantations in Trinidad because slavery was over and Trinidad was one of those

00:12:48.220 --> 00:12:53.540
[Guest]: islands where any were any Africans who were freed had other options this was a

00:12:53.540 --> 00:12:57.960
[Guest]: large enough place it wasn't like say Barbados where there was nowhere to go

00:12:57.960 --> 00:13:04.020
[Guest]: so you stayed on the estate so whenever there were options and Africans could

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:09.160
[Guest]: either set up their own communities in other parts more remote parts of the

00:13:09.160 --> 00:13:15.240
[Guest]: island there was no labor so Indians were brought over among them my family

00:13:15.240 --> 00:13:23.500
[Guest]: and in fact when I think of where we came from when I went to India I used the

00:13:23.500 --> 00:13:29.680
[Guest]: word I said okay I know it's somewhere Faisalabad but the town mentioned is

00:13:29.680 --> 00:13:34.720
[Guest]: Ajodhapur is there a place near Faisalabad by that name say Ayodhya

00:13:34.720 --> 00:13:42.700
[Guest]: that you're from Ayodhya yes and I still can speak like that and that was some of

00:13:42.700 --> 00:13:47.260
[Guest]: my earlier work but let's see if I can get you back to what it was like in a

00:13:47.260 --> 00:13:54.820
[Guest]: joint family where you're hearing Hindi you're hearing Bhojpuri because the old

00:13:54.820 --> 00:14:01.620
[Guest]: ones would speak to older people who came in in this dialect Spanish was very

00:14:01.620 --> 00:14:07.500
[Guest]: close you could see Venezuela from some parts of Trinidad in fact if you logged

00:14:07.500 --> 00:14:10.980
[Guest]: on a few minutes earlier you'd have heard me speaking in Spanish to someone

00:14:10.980 --> 00:14:16.620
[Guest]: here I'm in Mexico and it's just sort of like going from being right-handed to

00:14:16.620 --> 00:14:23.740
[Guest]: being left-handed and French I studied but my mother was spent part of a life

00:14:23.740 --> 00:14:28.860
[Guest]: in Quebec so I knew French also so there were all these things going on I studied

00:14:28.860 --> 00:14:34.620
[Guest]: Latin my father loved Latin so the European type languages and Creole were

00:14:34.620 --> 00:14:39.380
[Guest]: very accessible to me I could understand them that's my first language was Creole

00:14:39.380 --> 00:14:45.740
[Guest]: Hindi and Bhojpuri were less so they were kept away from me and I was

00:14:45.740 --> 00:14:51.820
[Guest]: resentful I kept wondering why can't I learn these things and they were

00:14:51.820 --> 00:14:57.300
[Guest]: desperately trying to see that I moved ahead into the modern world and not

00:14:57.300 --> 00:15:03.700
[Guest]: backward into whatever life we'd had before and it's only when I started

00:15:03.700 --> 00:15:10.100
[Guest]: doing linguistics and opting to study Bhojpuri and learning Hindi a little

00:15:10.100 --> 00:15:15.620
[Guest]: bit here and there from courses that they kind of figured that I wasn't going

00:15:15.620 --> 00:15:22.820
[Guest]: to backslide into being a bonded laborer and they helped me a little and so much

00:15:22.820 --> 00:15:27.060
[Guest]: so that my great-grandfather said to me okay you can learn Devanagari if

00:15:27.060 --> 00:15:31.500
[Guest]: you want learn it on your own I'm going to teach you something else and he

00:15:31.500 --> 00:15:37.420
[Guest]: taught me an almost extinct script called Kayathi which you might have

00:15:37.420 --> 00:15:43.460
[Guest]: heard of which is for very little seen in India and I would sit there forming

00:15:43.460 --> 00:15:51.180
[Guest]: the letters as a child and thinking that India was something that I knew about

00:15:51.180 --> 00:15:57.420
[Guest]: from my grandmother and great-grandfather so all of this was going on I did

00:15:57.420 --> 00:16:03.100
[Guest]: linguistics and that was a time in the West Indies when the whole Creole thing

00:16:03.100 --> 00:16:09.660
[Guest]: was coming up and the language that we thought was just bad English or bad

00:16:09.660 --> 00:16:16.220
[Guest]: French was suddenly being seen as an interesting hybrid and since we knew the

00:16:16.220 --> 00:16:20.860
[Guest]: history on the one hand of slavery and on the other hand we could look at these

00:16:20.860 --> 00:16:26.780
[Guest]: languages and we could see exactly what us the tiramisu bear look that I had

00:16:26.780 --> 00:16:33.820
[Guest]: mentioned in the beginning so this was going on all around me and as I did

00:16:33.820 --> 00:16:40.580
[Guest]: linguistics in the West Indies and then I went on to University of Michigan to

00:16:40.580 --> 00:16:46.420
[Guest]: do my PhD in linguistics ideas what should I do so I've done a lot of

00:16:46.420 --> 00:16:49.940
[Guest]: linguistics courses so one of the things I thought I might as well get in with

00:16:49.940 --> 00:16:55.100
[Guest]: you know as it is scoring subject to have some Sanskrit so I got into

00:16:55.100 --> 00:17:03.260
[Guest]: Sanskrit was it was scoring but I mean I worked non-stop at it I had to actually

00:17:03.260 --> 00:17:09.580
[Guest]: pull myself away from it to get on with writing a dissertation myself and then I

00:17:09.580 --> 00:17:14.460
[Guest]: decided that I would get back to the Caribbean work on the language that

00:17:14.460 --> 00:17:19.860
[Guest]: Indians had taken there and first describe it and then look at something

00:17:19.860 --> 00:17:24.020
[Guest]: completely different from how languages are born I looked at how they died do

00:17:24.020 --> 00:17:30.020
[Guest]: they all die in the same way do they die quickly or do they die gradually all

00:17:30.020 --> 00:17:34.220
[Guest]: these were questions that were coming up and they were linked also to do

00:17:34.220 --> 00:17:41.380
[Guest]: languages come up gradually or do they just within a generation emerge into the

00:17:41.380 --> 00:17:46.820
[Guest]: sunlight so these were the kinds of things that were going on in my mind

00:17:46.820 --> 00:17:52.060
[Guest]: growing up I must have had some interest in language because as a child I

00:17:52.060 --> 00:17:57.700
[Guest]: remember the moment standing in our backyard when I first pronounced her and

00:17:57.700 --> 00:18:02.900
[Guest]: I knew that I was not a baby anymore it was not actually her that was being

00:18:02.900 --> 00:18:08.900
[Guest]: passed off as and you to remember that you're about six or seven years old and

00:18:08.900 --> 00:18:14.300
[Guest]: the first time you make a difficult sound so clearly I was on my way to

00:18:14.300 --> 00:18:18.780
[Amit Varma]: being a linguist you have many fascinating strands and by the way you

00:18:18.780 --> 00:18:21.820
[Amit Varma]: mentioned Kathy and in your book you've got a lovely sort of illustration of

00:18:21.820 --> 00:18:25.340
[Amit Varma]: what Kathy is like and you point out how Kathy at one time was the most popular

00:18:25.340 --> 00:18:29.600
[Amit Varma]: script for writing Hindi and it wasn't Devanagari Devanagari came later and you

00:18:29.600 --> 00:18:33.780
[Amit Varma]: know one of the things I realize when I read about history is how much it seems

00:18:33.780 --> 00:18:38.340
[Amit Varma]: to us that everything that is perhaps a convention in the present time it almost

00:18:38.340 --> 00:18:42.220
[Amit Varma]: feels in our mind as if it must have always been the case whereas actually

00:18:42.220 --> 00:18:45.180
[Amit Varma]: what we are looking at is just a snapshot the things have changed

00:18:45.180 --> 00:18:49.700
[Amit Varma]: radically so fast and if you just go a little bit back in time you know things

00:18:49.700 --> 00:18:53.580
[Amit Varma]: were actually incredibly different and everything we take for granted was you

00:18:53.580 --> 00:18:57.660
[Amit Varma]: know almost came about through a variety of different accidents coming together

00:18:57.660 --> 00:19:02.540
[Amit Varma]: and creating a perfect storm which kind of brings you here before I get back on

00:19:02.540 --> 00:19:07.820
[Amit Varma]: you know asking about your personal arc a broader question also about language

00:19:07.820 --> 00:19:12.380
[Amit Varma]: which I have thought about a bit but I've never actually managed to speak

00:19:12.380 --> 00:19:16.140
[Amit Varma]: with an expert and actually bring this question up which is that just as

00:19:16.140 --> 00:19:21.700
[Amit Varma]: someone who reads a lot and mostly in translation obviously except you know I

00:19:21.700 --> 00:19:25.180
[Amit Varma]: can read Hindi but otherwise I'm reading all other languages translated into

00:19:25.180 --> 00:19:30.940
[Amit Varma]: English it strikes me that different languages have different essences so to

00:19:30.940 --> 00:19:35.860
[Amit Varma]: say which makes them almost in a sense untranslatable I did an episode on

00:19:35.860 --> 00:19:39.540
[Amit Varma]: translation with the translator Aruna Vasina who translates from Bengali to

00:19:39.540 --> 00:19:43.140
[Amit Varma]: English and this is one of the things we discussed where it strikes me that if

00:19:43.140 --> 00:19:46.340
[Amit Varma]: you look at the literature in some languages like Japanese and Korean

00:19:46.340 --> 00:19:51.180
[Amit Varma]: they'll tend to be very kind of stark and minimal and spare while if you look

00:19:51.180 --> 00:19:54.100
[Amit Varma]: at other languages like Urdu and Bengali you know they're very

00:19:54.100 --> 00:19:58.020
[Amit Varma]: expressionistic and maximalist and all of that and if you were to just do a

00:19:58.020 --> 00:20:02.060
[Amit Varma]: direct word-for-word translation into a language like English which kind of has

00:20:02.060 --> 00:20:06.980
[Amit Varma]: values of its own and all of that it would seem incredibly odd so the

00:20:06.980 --> 00:20:12.260
[Amit Varma]: question that sort of strikes me is that one I'm sure you'd agree that languages

00:20:12.260 --> 00:20:17.300
[Amit Varma]: do have different essences and all of that but where does that arise from like

00:20:17.300 --> 00:20:22.140
[Amit Varma]: does sound play a big part in that just the way that they sound and does that

00:20:22.140 --> 00:20:27.220
[Amit Varma]: then have consequences down the road you know because of the character or what

00:20:27.220 --> 00:20:30.780
[Amit Varma]: you can express is shaped by the language then you would expect that the

00:20:30.780 --> 00:20:37.020
[Amit Varma]: character of a society or a people is also shaped by that and we often don't

00:20:37.020 --> 00:20:40.740
[Amit Varma]: think about this now you're someone who's not only grown up in a very

00:20:40.740 --> 00:20:45.660
[Amit Varma]: multilingual environment but you've also traveled a lot lived in different parts

00:20:45.660 --> 00:20:49.900
[Amit Varma]: of the world and studied language so what are your sort of thoughts on this

00:20:49.900 --> 00:20:56.780
[Guest]: see I wouldn't go so far as to say it's the sounds the sounds are there of

00:20:56.780 --> 00:21:01.820
[Guest]: course but it is true that languages have a very different I think you use the

00:21:01.820 --> 00:21:06.060
[Guest]: word essence sort of that that's a good word because today on my Facebook feeds

00:21:06.060 --> 00:21:12.220
[Guest]: came up something I had written some years ago for Biblio and I was it

00:21:12.220 --> 00:21:18.740
[Guest]: started with me comparing what I had read as a 17 year old in Spanish as part

00:21:18.740 --> 00:21:25.380
[Guest]: of being a student of BA Spanish French linguistics a hundred years of solitude

00:21:25.380 --> 00:21:33.820
[Guest]: I read it and it seemed like every other book I read in Spanish because I was

00:21:33.820 --> 00:21:39.180
[Guest]: just very familiar with what everybody else exalts over now and calls magic

00:21:39.180 --> 00:21:43.820
[Guest]: realism it just seemed like since the 14th 15th century that's the kind of

00:21:43.820 --> 00:21:49.140
[Guest]: stuff that they have been writing so I read through it and didn't think much

00:21:49.140 --> 00:21:55.100
[Guest]: and then my daughter many years later said it's an awesome book and she'd read

00:21:55.100 --> 00:22:00.380
[Guest]: it in English and I decided to read it in English and the strangeness and the

00:22:00.380 --> 00:22:06.020
[Guest]: eeriness came out only in the translation because until then it was

00:22:06.020 --> 00:22:12.380
[Guest]: just a simple normal way that one writes in Spanish be it writers from Cuba

00:22:12.380 --> 00:22:17.340
[Guest]: writers from Spain writers from different parts of Latin America he just

00:22:17.340 --> 00:22:26.900
[Guest]: got very spotlighted and the normalcy of that kind of style or the way he

00:22:26.900 --> 00:22:31.700
[Guest]: expressed himself just didn't come out in English in fact it came out as a plus

00:22:31.700 --> 00:22:39.300
[Guest]: it looked Wow magic and it wasn't magic it's just a way everyone seemed to write

00:22:39.300 --> 00:22:44.500
[Guest]: so that's very hard to put across to people that the first time I read a

00:22:44.500 --> 00:22:50.900
[Guest]: hundred years of solitude it was just it was a pale echo of some of the other

00:22:50.900 --> 00:22:57.580
[Guest]: writers I had liked from Latin America because they all had this quality of the

00:22:57.580 --> 00:23:03.060
[Guest]: grotesque in the writing and that had to do I think it's more to do with a kind

00:23:03.060 --> 00:23:09.820
[Guest]: of social situation you grew up in a sense of hopelessness at times you see

00:23:09.820 --> 00:23:17.700
[Guest]: for example why did Ghalib write the way he did I mean don't you now in a fraught

00:23:17.700 --> 00:23:23.660
[Guest]: political situation find yourself writing cryptically and not completing

00:23:23.660 --> 00:23:29.540
[Guest]: words or using allusions rather than direct words so a lot of this has to do

00:23:29.540 --> 00:23:38.700
[Guest]: with the milieu you're writing in as to speech I can't say of course there are a

00:23:38.700 --> 00:23:43.460
[Guest]: lot of other things going on why do some languages sound different from others

00:23:43.460 --> 00:23:48.180
[Guest]: well there are lots of reasons for it why does Bengali sound different from

00:23:48.180 --> 00:23:54.500
[Guest]: Hindi completely different antecedents because the migrations into Bengal were

00:23:54.500 --> 00:24:01.380
[Guest]: quite different from the migrations that made their way towards Delhi so all of

00:24:01.380 --> 00:24:05.740
[Guest]: that colors the kind of character language would have I would say the

00:24:05.740 --> 00:24:12.100
[Guest]: sounds started the sounds may capture a bit of it but it starts from a much more

00:24:12.100 --> 00:24:18.540
[Amit Varma]: complex place yeah I mean multifactorial and and and just speaking of you know

00:24:18.540 --> 00:24:22.180
[Amit Varma]: hundred years of solitude I think it was translated by Gregory Rabasa and and a

00:24:22.180 --> 00:24:27.420
[Amit Varma]: lot of people hold Rabasa sort of in tremendous regard because they feel that

00:24:27.420 --> 00:24:31.980
[Amit Varma]: the translation is almost like a new creation of its own and I often yeah and

00:24:31.980 --> 00:24:35.980
[Amit Varma]: I often see that in you know a lot of the some of the Indian translators who

00:24:35.980 --> 00:24:39.340
[Amit Varma]: translate from languages which I would have thought that you know how do you

00:24:39.340 --> 00:24:42.500
[Amit Varma]: even translate it but if you look at you know Arvind Krishnamoorthra

00:24:42.500 --> 00:24:46.700
[Amit Varma]: translating Kabir or Ranjith Hoskote translating Lal Dey and it's just as if

00:24:46.700 --> 00:24:50.300
[Amit Varma]: they've created some magic of their own they haven't just done a literal

00:24:50.300 --> 00:24:54.380
[Amit Varma]: translation because that would simply not work but they've created a magic of

00:24:54.380 --> 00:24:58.260
[Amit Varma]: their own with what they've done which is fascinating so just kind of going

00:24:58.260 --> 00:25:02.980
[Amit Varma]: back to your personal journey it again growing up what was your conception of

00:25:02.980 --> 00:25:06.460
[Amit Varma]: yourself and how did it differ from the other kids around you with whom you're

00:25:06.460 --> 00:25:11.700
[Amit Varma]: going to school because obviously you've got kind of more influences coming in

00:25:11.700 --> 00:25:15.900
[Amit Varma]: from different places where your mother is a polar bear as you say in the

00:25:15.900 --> 00:25:20.380
[Amit Varma]: metaphor to take the metaphor forward and your whole family has that history

00:25:20.380 --> 00:25:23.940
[Amit Varma]: of speaking Bhojpuri Hindi they're from a different place and you're there in

00:25:23.940 --> 00:25:29.820
[Amit Varma]: the Caribbean and does it shape your view of the world in a way that is then

00:25:29.820 --> 00:25:35.220
[Amit Varma]: conducive towards becoming the sort of person that you would later become where

00:25:35.220 --> 00:25:38.460
[Amit Varma]: you're traveling the world and an international citizen of sorts with the

00:25:38.460 --> 00:25:42.660
[Amit Varma]: curiosity towards other cultures so did you feel that there was that difference

00:25:42.660 --> 00:25:47.740
[Amit Varma]: and that that difference was a fortuitous thing in terms of shaping

00:25:47.740 --> 00:25:52.180
[Amit Varma]: what you would go on to do and all of those things that's hard to say maybe

00:25:52.180 --> 00:25:59.220
[Guest]: the final outcome yes as a young child I would look in the mirror and say that

00:25:59.220 --> 00:26:03.980
[Guest]: what I saw didn't look like any of the things that are supposed to be there I

00:26:03.980 --> 00:26:11.260
[Guest]: didn't see an Indian and I definitely did not want to see a Canadian I was

00:26:11.260 --> 00:26:16.140
[Guest]: Caribbean but I didn't look like a lot of other Caribbeans so I had to put the

00:26:16.140 --> 00:26:21.660
[Guest]: whole question in a box and hide it away for some years until I was able to deal

00:26:21.660 --> 00:26:26.380
[Guest]: in any way with it maybe I haven't even taken it out of the box I've just let it

00:26:26.380 --> 00:26:33.260
[Guest]: continue and in India for a long time I have an Indian passport and people would

00:26:33.260 --> 00:26:38.460
[Guest]: ask me where are you from and I'd say Delhi because I've lived in Delhi for

00:26:38.460 --> 00:26:44.300
[Guest]: what more than 40 years and I'd feel hurt when people would say no but where

00:26:44.300 --> 00:26:50.020
[Guest]: are you really from you know everywhere I'd go I would try to blend in in some

00:26:50.020 --> 00:26:55.460
[Guest]: way which is why like when I hear people telling me in Mexico your Spanish has no

00:26:55.460 --> 00:27:01.980
[Guest]: accent is it what you mean no accent my Hindi has no accent to some extent I

00:27:01.980 --> 00:27:08.380
[Guest]: guess I'm told that my objective has always been to try to find a home for

00:27:08.380 --> 00:27:14.860
[Guest]: myself wherever I go to fit in until one day my daughter said to me why are you

00:27:14.860 --> 00:27:19.860
[Guest]: doing this you know when people ask you in India where are you from make their

00:27:19.860 --> 00:27:24.980
[Guest]: day it's the first time they've met a foreigner from an exotic place who can

00:27:24.980 --> 00:27:29.780
[Guest]: speak to them so just tell them you're from the Caribbean that'll satisfy them

00:27:29.780 --> 00:27:34.460
[Guest]: and so people think okay she's from the Caribbean and then they meet someone

00:27:34.460 --> 00:27:39.220
[Guest]: else from the Caribbean who's not like me at all so it's not one of those

00:27:39.220 --> 00:27:45.980
[Guest]: things that's easy to resolve what my identity is or except that because I've

00:27:45.980 --> 00:27:51.460
[Guest]: tried so hard like I took my time learning Hindi I didn't want to ever

00:27:51.460 --> 00:27:58.860
[Guest]: make any mistakes I didn't want anyone to listen to it and say be able to make

00:27:58.860 --> 00:28:04.540
[Guest]: out that you're from somewhere else so perhaps it made me a little bit more

00:28:04.540 --> 00:28:09.220
[Guest]: cautious there are people who just bluster in and just start speaking

00:28:09.220 --> 00:28:14.940
[Guest]: mistakes and all that wasn't for me because it was a something much more

00:28:14.940 --> 00:28:19.420
[Guest]: complex going on it was a bonding with the place and you can't bond with the

00:28:19.420 --> 00:28:25.820
[Guest]: place making mistakes you have to really have the operating system properly in

00:28:25.820 --> 00:28:32.380
[Guest]: the head I took time Hindi doesn't give itself up very easily and worse yet

00:28:32.380 --> 00:28:37.500
[Guest]: Malayalam I've reached a stage where I could pronounce Malayalam Malayalam and

00:28:37.500 --> 00:28:45.380
[Guest]: not have everybody say you got it wrong yeah no my mind was actually blown by

00:28:45.380 --> 00:28:48.900
[Amit Varma]: some of the things in your book because I know Hindi and I understand Marathi

00:28:48.900 --> 00:28:52.820
[Amit Varma]: and I was actually learning things about grammar and looking at things in new way

00:28:52.820 --> 00:28:56.300
[Amit Varma]: from some of the illuminations in your book so that was great you know the

00:28:56.300 --> 00:29:00.460
[Amit Varma]: thrust of my question or my observation or whatever also came from this notion

00:29:00.460 --> 00:29:05.940
[Amit Varma]: that people who are certain of their identity are often also straightjacketed

00:29:05.940 --> 00:29:10.060
[Amit Varma]: by it not just straightjacketed by it in terms of who they are but also in terms

00:29:10.060 --> 00:29:14.460
[Amit Varma]: of how they look at others which is why it will be a common question for them to

00:29:14.460 --> 00:29:19.780
[Amit Varma]: ask others where are you from or what is your village as the case might be and

00:29:19.780 --> 00:29:25.540
[Amit Varma]: and and in one sense I can of course understand the angst of not being

00:29:25.540 --> 00:29:30.700
[Amit Varma]: certain of one's identity but it it I feel like it is also in other ways

00:29:30.700 --> 00:29:34.060
[Amit Varma]: liberating and liberating in ways that you don't realize it because a lot of

00:29:34.060 --> 00:29:37.060
[Amit Varma]: people who are straightjacketed by identity in different ways may not

00:29:37.060 --> 00:29:40.500
[Amit Varma]: realize that they are constrained in some way that you know they contain

00:29:40.500 --> 00:29:45.780
[Amit Varma]: multitudes but they are thinking of themselves as only one thing so how did

00:29:45.780 --> 00:29:49.820
[Amit Varma]: you get into linguistics from here like when you were a kid what did you want to

00:29:49.820 --> 00:29:53.740
[Amit Varma]: be and was it just the case that you know you went to college and you found

00:29:53.740 --> 00:29:59.660
[Guest]: this an interesting subject and it wasn't when I was 12 years old I think

00:29:59.660 --> 00:30:06.300
[Guest]: Time magazine run an issue on Noam Chomsky and I decided right then and

00:30:06.300 --> 00:30:12.340
[Guest]: there that all my interest since about the age of eight or so in languages and

00:30:12.340 --> 00:30:19.700
[Guest]: how they looked alike could be something far more serious than just philology and

00:30:19.700 --> 00:30:25.380
[Guest]: knowing languages or translating I saw what he was talking about deep

00:30:25.380 --> 00:30:30.100
[Guest]: structure was one thing I started reading up a bit about him and you have

00:30:30.100 --> 00:30:34.420
[Guest]: no idea what it's like to read Chomsky as a young person sometimes I

00:30:34.420 --> 00:30:38.900
[Guest]: would end up reading a page five times to get what he was saying he's not a

00:30:38.900 --> 00:30:45.340
[Guest]: great writer actually but his ideas are very good so somewhere around then I

00:30:45.340 --> 00:30:51.220
[Guest]: decided that I was going to be a linguist and my mother said but from the

00:30:51.220 --> 00:30:55.660
[Guest]: sound of what these people are doing in MIT don't you have to be a science

00:30:55.660 --> 00:31:03.220
[Guest]: student and I said maybe not let's see but if I need to learn some science for

00:31:03.220 --> 00:31:07.740
[Guest]: it I will and as it is you do have to learn some physiology to learn the whole

00:31:07.740 --> 00:31:12.780
[Guest]: vocal tract you have to learn a certain amount about the brain because it's all

00:31:12.780 --> 00:31:17.440
[Guest]: processed in the brain so suddenly you find yourself very comfortable talking

00:31:17.440 --> 00:31:22.380
[Guest]: to medical people or the notion of an operating system and understanding how

00:31:22.380 --> 00:31:30.820
[Guest]: computers work because the brain does have a number of those features so from

00:31:30.820 --> 00:31:35.380
[Guest]: the time I was 12 I knew I was going to do linguistics and my father worked at

00:31:35.380 --> 00:31:38.700
[Guest]: the University of the West Indies and told me a lot about the linguistics

00:31:38.700 --> 00:31:42.540
[Guest]: department there and I knew who the professors were going to be and

00:31:42.540 --> 00:31:50.220
[Guest]: everything and I knew that's where I was headed so and then afterwards I wanted

00:31:50.220 --> 00:31:56.340
[Guest]: to go abroad and do a PhD and I'm actually glad it ended up being the

00:31:56.340 --> 00:32:00.940
[Guest]: University of Michigan because if I'd gone somewhere like Stanford or Harvard

00:32:00.940 --> 00:32:06.020
[Guest]: I might have been pushed into much more theoretical work which didn't draw on

00:32:06.020 --> 00:32:12.300
[Guest]: the things I already knew about which is like hybridization Creole languages

00:32:12.300 --> 00:32:18.980
[Guest]: Indian languages dying languages languages being born so I always wanted

00:32:18.980 --> 00:32:26.340
[Guest]: to do this and I veered away from it for a while in India because job wise until

00:32:26.340 --> 00:32:31.340
[Guest]: I got an Indian passport it wasn't really possible to get a permanent job

00:32:31.340 --> 00:32:38.380
[Guest]: as a linguist so now I'm putting out all the things that I've been thinking of

00:32:38.380 --> 00:32:44.980
[Guest]: all these years which and it's just a sometimes surprising to me that all

00:32:44.980 --> 00:32:50.380
[Guest]: these questions didn't work occur to a whole lot of other people because many

00:32:50.380 --> 00:32:57.300
[Guest]: people are working on all these issues to do with Indian languages and somehow

00:32:57.300 --> 00:33:03.580
[Guest]: they don't ask that bold question why why are they like this not what are they

00:33:03.580 --> 00:33:09.820
[Guest]: like but why what does this tell us about the past it's a bit of a leap and

00:33:09.820 --> 00:33:16.260
[Guest]: I think you just have to be a little bit brave or foolish to jump into these

00:33:16.260 --> 00:33:23.060
[Amit Varma]: questions so what I loved about your book was about how through language

00:33:23.060 --> 00:33:26.860
[Amit Varma]: almost carrying out a forensic act as it were how through language you've looked

00:33:26.860 --> 00:33:30.940
[Amit Varma]: at history you looked at humanity you know it reveals so much about us not

00:33:30.940 --> 00:33:35.540
[Amit Varma]: just about our history but perhaps even about our essential nature and so on and

00:33:35.540 --> 00:33:39.660
[Amit Varma]: so forth how we respond to incentives how politics plays a part you met you

00:33:39.660 --> 00:33:43.420
[Amit Varma]: know you contrasted Amir Khusrow and Ghalib which is quite a sort of stunning

00:33:43.420 --> 00:33:48.220
[Amit Varma]: and revelatory contrast there and my question is that when you started out in

00:33:48.220 --> 00:33:53.140
[Amit Varma]: linguistics at that time what was a field like like I discovered Chomsky's

00:33:53.140 --> 00:33:56.180
[Amit Varma]: work through reading Steven Pinker's The Language Instinct and then went down

00:33:56.180 --> 00:34:00.220
[Unknown]: that kind of rabbit hole where I read up a little bit and all of it was very

00:34:00.220 --> 00:34:03.500
[Amit Varma]: fascinating the innate structures and how we deal with language and all of

00:34:03.500 --> 00:34:08.620
[Amit Varma]: that but I haven't really come across much work of the kind that is in your

00:34:08.620 --> 00:34:12.940
[Amit Varma]: book which is possibly and just an illustration of how ill-read I am but

00:34:12.940 --> 00:34:16.260
[Amit Varma]: tell me a bit about the linguistics profession itself and how it has evolved

00:34:16.260 --> 00:34:20.660
[Amit Varma]: because one of the things that strikes me and certainly in fields that I know a

00:34:20.660 --> 00:34:24.980
[Amit Varma]: little bit more about like economics or political theory or whatever one of the

00:34:24.980 --> 00:34:28.780
[Amit Varma]: things you do realize is that within academia there are often these trends

00:34:28.780 --> 00:34:32.740
[Amit Varma]: and fashions and you know leitmotifs of the time which carry through and they

00:34:32.740 --> 00:34:36.940
[Amit Varma]: there's a subtle pressure on new people coming into those field to do certain

00:34:36.940 --> 00:34:40.780
[Amit Varma]: things and not do other things and to follow certain lines of inquiry and not

00:34:40.780 --> 00:34:45.380
[Amit Varma]: follow others was there something like that in linguistics watch what were your

00:34:45.380 --> 00:34:49.140
[Amit Varma]: natural interests did you feel constrained at any point give me a sense

00:34:49.140 --> 00:34:54.260
[Amit Varma]: of the evolution of the field over the last 30 40 years okay our first year was

00:34:54.260 --> 00:34:59.300
[Guest]: very simple you have to learn the nuts and bolts of phonetics phonemics

00:34:59.300 --> 00:35:04.620
[Guest]: morphology they throw you problems with languages you've never seen before like

00:35:04.620 --> 00:35:12.020
[Guest]: Turkish or Swahili those are favored ones because they're easy enough to cut

00:35:12.020 --> 00:35:18.660
[Guest]: in you know and segment and see this ending refers to this so we learn the

00:35:18.660 --> 00:35:24.820
[Guest]: nuts and bolts of linguistics first and by the second year we were getting

00:35:24.820 --> 00:35:28.940
[Guest]: exposed to the kind of professors who were working on hybridization

00:35:28.940 --> 00:35:35.780
[Guest]: creolization and various aspects of it how the languages came into existence

00:35:35.780 --> 00:35:41.580
[Guest]: was one and the other one was how they were changing in real time something

00:35:41.580 --> 00:35:46.780
[Guest]: similar to the Hinglish continuum you're getting in Hindi and English in North

00:35:46.780 --> 00:35:51.900
[Guest]: India we get that in the Caribbean so trying to understand how people make

00:35:51.900 --> 00:35:58.860
[Guest]: slow transitions from simply one language to another so these were two

00:35:58.860 --> 00:36:03.140
[Guest]: big things that were happening in the Caribbean at that time one got sucked

00:36:03.140 --> 00:36:08.740
[Guest]: into it and I don't think I resisted it because I found it very exciting because

00:36:08.740 --> 00:36:13.700
[Guest]: all of a sudden here you are a young student undergraduate with the kind of

00:36:13.700 --> 00:36:18.540
[Guest]: people who are shaping an important part of the field and here you are in it and

00:36:18.540 --> 00:36:25.940
[Guest]: I got out of it in a way by getting into the Indian language that we spoke which

00:36:25.940 --> 00:36:32.740
[Guest]: is Bhojpuri and that had to be done but to eventually be able to back off and

00:36:32.740 --> 00:36:37.820
[Guest]: pull the whole thing together was something that I dreamed of doing for

00:36:37.820 --> 00:36:42.820
[Guest]: all these years I've been sitting doing other things and looking at it out of

00:36:42.820 --> 00:36:48.060
[Guest]: the corner of my eye the field of linguistics has undergone all kinds of

00:36:48.060 --> 00:36:53.660
[Guest]: changes from the excitement of Chomsky and that language was very much

00:36:53.660 --> 00:36:58.700
[Guest]: associated with how the brain functioned and located in various parts of the

00:36:58.700 --> 00:37:07.180
[Guest]: brain all of that was a season and then came the cutbacks in the budgets and all

00:37:07.180 --> 00:37:13.300
[Guest]: sorts of things stopped being done in the US we were pushed towards very functional

00:37:13.300 --> 00:37:19.940
[Guest]: things like how to teach English to foreigners or how to deal with language

00:37:19.940 --> 00:37:25.140
[Guest]: for computational purposes it got a little bit dry but there was one beauty

00:37:25.140 --> 00:37:31.380
[Guest]: to linguistics which kept me in it which is it doesn't cost much if you have to

00:37:31.380 --> 00:37:36.660
[Guest]: do research you don't have to set up a Hadron Collider or something there's no

00:37:36.660 --> 00:37:43.780
[Guest]: huge budget involved and while travel could be an issue nowadays it isn't

00:37:43.780 --> 00:37:51.300
[Guest]: really you want to find out a paper about an obscure language of the Native

00:37:51.300 --> 00:37:56.940
[Guest]: Americans in the west of Canada you just go online you go on Facebook you find

00:37:56.940 --> 00:38:02.460
[Guest]: someone who's actually done the work when I wanted to crack a few sentences

00:38:02.460 --> 00:38:08.780
[Guest]: in Malayalam from a YouTube thing that I had I had a friend who knew Malayalam

00:38:08.780 --> 00:38:15.500
[Guest]: and was helping me we just went on on whatsapp we were able to do it sitting

00:38:15.500 --> 00:38:21.180
[Guest]: each in our own homes going on to voice recording but when I wanted to crack the

00:38:21.180 --> 00:38:28.620
[Guest]: chagatai the opening bits of Baburnama I had a friend in Delhi who is from

00:38:28.620 --> 00:38:35.780
[Guest]: Azerbaijan and she and I sat again on whatsapp and she said I don't know how

00:38:35.780 --> 00:38:40.580
[Guest]: to describe this sound but I'm gonna just record it for you and and she

00:38:40.580 --> 00:38:46.940
[Guest]: recorded I said oh my god is this how he spoke I thought this was extinct in that

00:38:46.940 --> 00:38:53.420
[Guest]: part of Central Asia Wow so there's so much that you can do without leaving

00:38:53.420 --> 00:39:00.100
[Guest]: your desk without spending a paisa you could really continue doing this kind of

00:39:00.100 --> 00:39:05.900
[Guest]: work and it was wonderful because given that in India grants for social sciences

00:39:05.900 --> 00:39:11.900
[Guest]: are sort of closing you know you're getting less and less possibility of

00:39:11.900 --> 00:39:17.940
[Guest]: doing this kind of work what was nice is that it could you could do it on your

00:39:17.940 --> 00:39:24.660
[Guest]: own dime so I continued so it didn't matter that this kind of linguistics was

00:39:24.660 --> 00:39:30.660
[Guest]: not being done much or not being encouraged by the granting system I just

00:39:30.660 --> 00:39:38.100
[Guest]: knew that I could continue and that in a way the field was open because a large

00:39:38.100 --> 00:39:43.980
[Guest]: number of people had simply left you you go by where the grant money is taking

00:39:43.980 --> 00:39:49.460
[Amit Varma]: you Wow and and and by the way everything that you said about

00:39:49.460 --> 00:39:53.500
[Amit Varma]: communicating with your friend on whatsapp and she recording the sound and

00:39:53.500 --> 00:39:57.900
[Amit Varma]: sending it to you it's just so amazing just feels so magical and beautiful to

00:39:57.900 --> 00:40:01.540
[Amit Varma]: me connecting like that and almost kind of bringing the dead alive through that

00:40:01.540 --> 00:40:05.940
[Amit Varma]: you know when when you kind of realize how Babur spoke during this time while

00:40:05.940 --> 00:40:11.260
[Amit Varma]: you were involved in all of this what kind of similar work are you looking at

00:40:11.260 --> 00:40:15.100
[Amit Varma]: from your own field or from other fields where you know a lot of the joy I

00:40:15.100 --> 00:40:19.100
[Amit Varma]: suppose comes from your own love of different languages and just the

00:40:19.100 --> 00:40:22.860
[Amit Varma]: intellectual excitement of figuring out how they work and how they evolve and

00:40:22.860 --> 00:40:28.420
[Amit Varma]: all of that but equally there is also that sense of opening doors through

00:40:28.420 --> 00:40:33.380
[Amit Varma]: language so were they precedents were there you know books or research that

00:40:33.380 --> 00:40:37.060
[Amit Varma]: really excited you and you said that you know this is the kind of thing I want to

00:40:37.060 --> 00:40:41.460
[Amit Varma]: do whether using language or whether using other forensic tools or other

00:40:41.460 --> 00:40:45.860
[Amit Varma]: frames of looking at it like in a popular writing you know Jared Diamond's

00:40:45.860 --> 00:40:50.180
[Amit Varma]: book of course you know gun germs and steels comes into play or but different

00:40:50.180 --> 00:40:53.780
[Amit Varma]: people have looked at the past through different prisms most recently you've

00:40:53.780 --> 00:40:58.180
[Amit Varma]: had you know all the work of looking at the past through genetics so you know

00:40:58.180 --> 00:41:02.740
[Amit Varma]: both in language and in other subjects were there people who kind of inspired

00:41:02.740 --> 00:41:06.740
[Amit Varma]: you and said that's the kind of thing I want to do this opened my mind you know

00:41:06.740 --> 00:41:12.140
[Amit Varma]: I want to do this is the work that inspires me yes but they generally

00:41:12.140 --> 00:41:15.420
[Guest]: weren't linguists they were all the people you're talking about the

00:41:15.420 --> 00:41:23.380
[Guest]: geneticists historians there were even people like Stephen Gould who worked on

00:41:23.380 --> 00:41:28.580
[Guest]: punctuated equilibria because I was finding my data on language death

00:41:28.580 --> 00:41:34.460
[Guest]: impossible to understand I wasn't seeing a slow gradient which you we were told

00:41:34.460 --> 00:41:39.100
[Guest]: was there I was finding people either spoke a language or didn't speak it and

00:41:39.100 --> 00:41:44.660
[Guest]: the only thing that helped was understanding evolutionary biology and

00:41:44.660 --> 00:41:52.940
[Guest]: why species would decline within a generation or come into existence within

00:41:52.940 --> 00:41:57.540
[Guest]: a generation languages were doing that too so the metaphor of a lot of other

00:41:57.540 --> 00:42:04.420
[Guest]: fields evolutionary biology now genetics there are few others little things of

00:42:04.420 --> 00:42:12.180
[Guest]: archaeology I didn't get so much history trying to understand patterns the Vedic

00:42:12.180 --> 00:42:16.940
[Guest]: era is quite far back but we have so many other things in India which were

00:42:16.940 --> 00:42:23.700
[Guest]: more recent like the migration into Assam the migration into Kerala that you

00:42:23.700 --> 00:42:27.580
[Guest]: could see that there were patterns somewhere that if similar things

00:42:27.580 --> 00:42:32.100
[Guest]: happened and similar inputs were there now this was not even strictly

00:42:32.100 --> 00:42:38.900
[Guest]: linguistics I don't even know how much of it is history how much of it is

00:42:38.900 --> 00:42:44.540
[Guest]: genetics but linguists were not writing about this sort of thing they were

00:42:44.540 --> 00:42:51.540
[Guest]: writing in smaller little compartments even some of the exciting work in

00:42:51.540 --> 00:42:56.780
[Guest]: Sanskrit was linked only to Sanskrit and the practice and so it wasn't looking

00:42:56.780 --> 00:43:02.500
[Guest]: beyond that that hey this happened subsequently in India you could get

00:43:02.500 --> 00:43:09.460
[Guest]: something out of looking at that too you know so I was looking at a number of

00:43:09.460 --> 00:43:17.580
[Guest]: linguists who were working in their tiny citadels and trying to bring it all

00:43:17.580 --> 00:43:22.060
[Guest]: together it's hard you know the specialization is something that's

00:43:22.060 --> 00:43:29.220
[Guest]: pretty much pushed on you but I felt that what was more interesting to me is

00:43:29.220 --> 00:43:34.380
[Guest]: to see how the whole thing worked as a pattern and how the moving parts

00:43:34.380 --> 00:43:42.060
[Guest]: functioned and for that I couldn't stick with just Sanskrit or look at I didn't

00:43:42.060 --> 00:43:47.900
[Guest]: really look at Assamese except to say that a very similar thing took place or

00:43:47.900 --> 00:43:54.020
[Guest]: in various other parts of India but yeah but these were all very different things

00:43:54.020 --> 00:43:58.220
[Amit Varma]: that happened. Yeah you mentioned Stephen Jay Gould and

00:43:58.220 --> 00:44:01.660
[Amit Varma]: and the first time I read something by Gould was he had written this fabulous

00:44:01.660 --> 00:44:05.380
[Amit Varma]: book on baseball statistics which is very odd you you won't imagine an

00:44:05.380 --> 00:44:09.980
[Amit Varma]: evolutionary biologist writing about baseball stats but it was just sort of a

00:44:09.980 --> 00:44:13.100
[Amit Varma]: new way of looking at that which I found interesting though in the Gould versus

00:44:13.100 --> 00:44:17.820
[Amit Varma]: Dawkins debate I kind of usually found myself sympathizing more with Dawkins

00:44:17.820 --> 00:44:21.580
[Amit Varma]: but the question here is that what people like Gould demonstrate and so

00:44:21.580 --> 00:44:25.500
[Amit Varma]: many other polymath thinkers demonstrate is that they can talk about different

00:44:25.500 --> 00:44:30.060
[Amit Varma]: subjects because you can take a frame from one subject and apply it to another

00:44:30.060 --> 00:44:33.580
[Amit Varma]: subject like even in your book you've got all these lovely metaphors like you

00:44:33.580 --> 00:44:37.760
[Amit Varma]: talk about you know Gould's concept of punctuated equilibria and how languages

00:44:37.760 --> 00:44:41.260
[Amit Varma]: show the same kind of thing which you know is going to be my next question to

00:44:41.260 --> 00:44:45.780
[Amit Varma]: you but before that my broader question to you is that is this something that is

00:44:45.780 --> 00:44:50.180
[Amit Varma]: inherent to you that taking frames from one subject and applying it to look at

00:44:50.180 --> 00:44:54.860
[Amit Varma]: the world in general and therefore having a kind of a broader view or is it

00:44:54.860 --> 00:44:59.180
[Amit Varma]: something that you feel necessary to cultivate and is it something that you

00:44:59.180 --> 00:45:03.620
[Amit Varma]: feel other thinkers and researchers necessarily don't do enough of that you

00:45:03.620 --> 00:45:07.940
[Amit Varma]: would advise young people to do that don't just focus on your field and get

00:45:07.940 --> 00:45:12.300
[Amit Varma]: really granular but step back a little bit take the broader view look at

00:45:12.300 --> 00:45:16.500
[Amit Varma]: society look at this look at that you know and and things will begin to make

00:45:16.500 --> 00:45:21.260
[Guest]: sense what are your thoughts on it two thoughts one is just as a dog walks

00:45:21.260 --> 00:45:28.180
[Guest]: around and perceives the universe through smell I can walk around on the

00:45:28.180 --> 00:45:35.980
[Guest]: barren landscapes of Mexico and see a replay of the Indus Valley civilization

00:45:35.980 --> 00:45:40.780
[Guest]: which we know nothing about really we don't even know what they call

00:45:40.780 --> 00:45:45.700
[Guest]: themselves and then earlier cultures of Mexico they don't even know what these

00:45:45.700 --> 00:45:50.140
[Guest]: people called themselves so you you have this sense that everywhere you go you

00:45:50.140 --> 00:45:57.220
[Guest]: sniff and what you sniff is this huge pattern in this universe as to whether

00:45:57.220 --> 00:46:03.780
[Guest]: people should get out of their boxes and do it it's hard to say everyone does

00:46:03.780 --> 00:46:10.940
[Guest]: what they can and perhaps you just need to see one person do it and be brave

00:46:10.940 --> 00:46:16.140
[Guest]: enough and not get slaughtered for it I am astonished that I haven't had more

00:46:16.140 --> 00:46:22.660
[Guest]: blows for some of the bold things that I've said young linguists would see that

00:46:22.660 --> 00:46:28.420
[Guest]: and probably feel well they've been thinking similar things too but haven't

00:46:28.420 --> 00:46:33.380
[Guest]: written them down because what kind of trouble will they get into they have

00:46:33.380 --> 00:46:38.980
[Guest]: that that is an issue and if you're in academia to write a book like mine might

00:46:38.980 --> 00:46:45.340
[Guest]: not get you the promotions you want although when you're my age to have a

00:46:45.340 --> 00:46:52.060
[Guest]: book that's much more accessible to the public is considered a good thing but

00:46:52.060 --> 00:47:01.140
[Guest]: not for a young person so as to whether they should do it well can they do it if

00:47:01.140 --> 00:47:07.700
[Guest]: you've been like you have no idea how much work has been done in India on the

00:47:07.700 --> 00:47:17.380
[Guest]: past tense in all the western parts of India starting with Goa Maharashtra all

00:47:17.380 --> 00:47:23.220
[Guest]: the way up through Rajasthan Gujarat the Hindi belt and separately all through

00:47:23.220 --> 00:47:30.460
[Guest]: Pakistan with no contact with each other people have studied these languages with

00:47:30.460 --> 00:47:36.540
[Guest]: this unusual past tense where the verb agrees with the object and nobody sort

00:47:36.540 --> 00:47:43.860
[Guest]: of asked why this belt what is it about this phenomenon people have said yes

00:47:43.860 --> 00:47:49.020
[Guest]: it's not the passive food eaten that's the favorite phrase there but nobody's

00:47:49.020 --> 00:47:55.180
[Guest]: tried to see why just this area and almost nowhere else so to take it

00:47:55.180 --> 00:48:01.200
[Guest]: further back requires the kind of thing that maybe academia wouldn't reward you

00:48:01.200 --> 00:48:10.540
[Guest]: for doing stick with the facts and just plod a little bit here and there they're

00:48:10.540 --> 00:48:15.500
[Guest]: good I mean these people they've done wonderful studies but to make that leap

00:48:15.500 --> 00:48:21.740
[Guest]: to say and add in southern Iran which no longer has it you're talking of the

00:48:21.740 --> 00:48:27.880
[Guest]: Harappan people and it's a wonderful exciting thought that all the things in

00:48:27.880 --> 00:48:33.760
[Guest]: Hindi that make no sense in terms of Sanskrit come from these same people

00:48:33.760 --> 00:48:42.620
[Guest]: that we have no way of finding we are them I found that's just so mind-blowing and then

00:48:42.620 --> 00:48:49.020
[Guest]: putting it up there right where you can shoot it down and nobody shot it down

00:48:49.020 --> 00:48:54.220
[Guest]: it's an exciting thought but now there are many more linguists in India I see

00:48:54.220 --> 00:49:00.780
[Guest]: all the time who could write all these sorts of things and probably were a

00:49:00.780 --> 00:49:09.140
[Guest]: little bit timid but they know enough to do it we probably see more of it you

00:49:09.140 --> 00:49:13.020
[Amit Varma]: know that's really interesting and it's heartening and it's a valid point that

00:49:13.020 --> 00:49:16.900
[Amit Varma]: you make that people are after all driven by incentives so on the one hand

00:49:16.900 --> 00:49:20.300
[Amit Varma]: I can imagine someone who's an academia you have the incentives or whatever the

00:49:20.300 --> 00:49:24.100
[Amit Varma]: fashions and trends of the academic world are but on the other hand if you're

00:49:24.100 --> 00:49:27.440
[Amit Varma]: a linguist in India do you really want to get into trouble at this point in

00:49:27.440 --> 00:49:32.580
[Amit Varma]: time by talking about you know how the Arya came into India for example and the

00:49:32.580 --> 00:49:36.500
[Amit Varma]: stuff that then went down or the fact that there is a Dravidian belt which

00:49:36.500 --> 00:49:40.380
[Amit Varma]: actually extends all the way from southern Iran all the way through you

00:49:40.380 --> 00:49:44.180
[Amit Varma]: know Afghanistan Pakistan and all the way to the south kind of bypassing Delhi

00:49:44.180 --> 00:49:50.140
[Amit Varma]: which is such a quite Delhi's in it Delhi's in it yeah you kind of said it's

00:49:50.140 --> 00:49:55.700
[Guest]: like shading Delhi's lately yeah if I remember yeah glance to Delhi and they're

00:49:55.700 --> 00:49:59.740
[Guest]: not not exactly the Dravidians you know from the south there's something

00:49:59.740 --> 00:50:05.140
[Amit Varma]: different again about them we don't know who they are yeah and and but that is so

00:50:05.140 --> 00:50:09.620
[Amit Varma]: counterintuitive and just saying something like that I imagine in present

00:50:09.620 --> 00:50:12.820
[Amit Varma]: day India would kind of get into trouble like I just think of all the

00:50:12.820 --> 00:50:17.220
[Amit Varma]: controversies poor Tony Joseph got into after writing early Indians it is based

00:50:17.220 --> 00:50:23.860
[Guest]: on such solid science but why I mean I'm surprised that he did I think that anyone

00:50:23.860 --> 00:50:31.180
[Guest]: okay I'm gonna take a little bold step here now I'm surprised I have got into

00:50:31.180 --> 00:50:38.180
[Guest]: no trouble I think partly I've just gone step by step and only stuck with what I

00:50:38.180 --> 00:50:44.340
[Guest]: can verify I wasn't yes like Tony Joseph here and there it's other people's

00:50:44.340 --> 00:50:54.580
[Guest]: research that one is dependent on but I have not overtly expressed a political

00:50:54.580 --> 00:51:00.620
[Guest]: position I have not tried to beat anyone I have not if anything I've offered you

00:51:00.620 --> 00:51:06.580
[Guest]: something better you want to be Aria I think that's real small time I'm so

00:51:06.580 --> 00:51:12.060
[Guest]: excited at being her up and I've given you something better you know and when

00:51:12.060 --> 00:51:18.020
[Guest]: you say did the Vedic people come to India or leave India and I show a

00:51:18.020 --> 00:51:23.340
[Guest]: pattern of a small settlement in the northwest it's beginning to spread

00:51:23.340 --> 00:51:29.980
[Guest]: eastwards and southward and there's a time dimension on it that something

00:51:29.980 --> 00:51:37.260
[Guest]: doesn't spread into India if it's the thing that an overtime if it's actually

00:51:37.260 --> 00:51:42.140
[Guest]: on the way out but I don't have to actually say it all you have to do is

00:51:42.140 --> 00:51:52.980
[Guest]: show the time that from 3700 years ago until when it reached Assam and then

00:51:52.980 --> 00:51:58.400
[Guest]: it's going further into Nagaland you're beginning to see things going up into

00:51:58.400 --> 00:52:05.420
[Guest]: Sikkim it's an ongoing process so if it's not even stopped how can you say

00:52:05.420 --> 00:52:11.100
[Guest]: that this was something that was always there in India and going out it doesn't

00:52:11.100 --> 00:52:16.700
[Guest]: make sense but at the same time I've been very clear that until the genetic

00:52:16.700 --> 00:52:23.140
[Guest]: studies came and of course looking at it in the way I just looked at it as an

00:52:23.140 --> 00:52:30.580
[Guest]: ongoing thing until all these genetic studies came there really was no idea

00:52:30.580 --> 00:52:34.460
[Guest]: where these people had come from and people were just throwing words around

00:52:34.460 --> 00:52:40.740
[Guest]: they were saying Caucasus, Caucasians what a stupid idea because the Caucasus

00:52:40.740 --> 00:52:48.340
[Guest]: has 50 languages of which only three are very iffily related to the Indo-Aryan

00:52:48.340 --> 00:52:54.740
[Guest]: languages why the Caucasus and then they start saying maybe Anatolia modern

00:52:54.740 --> 00:53:00.700
[Guest]: Turkey all of these were guesses and they talked about Indo-Germanic come on

00:53:00.700 --> 00:53:09.580
[Guest]: come on no there was this strong feeling of the colonial era where white people

00:53:09.580 --> 00:53:13.220
[Guest]: wanted to say that if there was something interesting about India it has

00:53:13.220 --> 00:53:18.660
[Guest]: to have come from Europe or somewhere like that so I why should one accept

00:53:18.660 --> 00:53:25.260
[Guest]: that and then later comes the idea of genetic studies which somewhat resolves

00:53:25.260 --> 00:53:31.020
[Guest]: it I think it pretty much resolves it for me and what the icing on the cake

00:53:31.020 --> 00:53:37.660
[Guest]: being that it's still ongoing and trickling into inward into India so

00:53:37.660 --> 00:53:45.620
[Guest]: having put it that way and not tried to bait anybody because I understand why

00:53:45.620 --> 00:53:52.620
[Guest]: they would be angry with the earlier notion that there were white people who

00:53:52.620 --> 00:53:58.100
[Guest]: came down into India and that and that they took over a huge belt of India now

00:53:58.100 --> 00:54:07.900
[Guest]: that that's that's racist stuff yeah so I suspect that that may be why I've seen

00:54:07.900 --> 00:54:15.340
[Guest]: people who are known to be supporters of out of India actually nodding as you're

00:54:15.340 --> 00:54:21.380
[Guest]: nodding now when they talk of some of what I've written and I'm just

00:54:21.380 --> 00:54:27.140
[Guest]: completely overwhelmed because it means that they're thinking about it and they

00:54:27.140 --> 00:54:33.500
[Guest]: don't feel in any way excluded or insulted which I don't mean them to be

00:54:33.500 --> 00:54:37.700
[Amit Varma]: does that make a kind of sense I'll come up with a counterpoint to that but

00:54:37.700 --> 00:54:41.100
[Amit Varma]: before that a quick note for my listeners that you know I've done a

00:54:41.100 --> 00:54:44.460
[Amit Varma]: great episode with Tony Joseph who's written the book early Indians a couple

00:54:44.460 --> 00:54:47.620
[Amit Varma]: of years back so I'll link it from the show notes and that kind of talks in

00:54:47.620 --> 00:54:53.380
[Amit Varma]: great detail about what we have learned in the last few years about our history

00:54:53.380 --> 00:54:57.900
[Amit Varma]: through looking at genetic evidence and which is pretty hard to argue with and a

00:54:57.900 --> 00:55:01.700
[Amit Varma]: very powerful that's an illuminating book and an illuminating episode as well

00:55:01.700 --> 00:55:05.620
[Amit Varma]: but my sort of counterpoint to that is when you say that I only wrote about

00:55:05.620 --> 00:55:09.980
[Amit Varma]: what I can verify the truth is not really the point here the point here is

00:55:09.980 --> 00:55:15.940
[Amit Varma]: narratives that there is a narrative based on nationalistic pride and it's

00:55:15.940 --> 00:55:20.420
[Amit Varma]: got a xenophobic element to it also where the whole narrative is you know

00:55:20.420 --> 00:55:24.420
[Amit Varma]: that somehow Aryans are supreme and the out of India theory that you referred to

00:55:24.420 --> 00:55:28.580
[Amit Varma]: of course is that there weren't Arya people coming from outside to India but

00:55:28.580 --> 00:55:32.900
[Amit Varma]: instead everything began in India Sanskrit is the motherlode and we went

00:55:32.900 --> 00:55:37.100
[Amit Varma]: out and everything comes from us and all of that which you know is there is a

00:55:37.100 --> 00:55:41.220
[Amit Varma]: sort of narrative of national pride and all that and anything that strikes us

00:55:41.220 --> 00:55:46.380
