[Amit Varma]: as in fact your book demonstrates more than any other but I was kind of curious

01:52:39.340 --> 01:52:43.180
[Amit Varma]: and I guess some things you know a certain kind of way of using a

01:52:43.180 --> 01:52:47.580
[Amit Varma]: participle could evolve as sort of just an evolutionary accident and then it

01:52:47.580 --> 01:52:51.900
[Amit Varma]: determines other things like the passive voice which flows from there and there

01:52:51.900 --> 01:52:56.940
[Amit Varma]: isn't necessarily deeper structure to that a deeper purpose to that particular

01:52:56.940 --> 01:53:01.220
[Amit Varma]: thing let's kind of go back for a moment to the Vedic invasion I was reading a

01:53:01.220 --> 01:53:05.260
[Amit Varma]: passage that you quoted from Jared Diamond in fact in gun germs and steel

01:53:05.260 --> 01:53:08.820
[Amit Varma]: which you quote in your book and a question struck me after reading that so

01:53:08.820 --> 01:53:12.860
[Amit Varma]: first I'll sort of read that out and then I'll ask my question where he's

01:53:12.860 --> 01:53:16.020
[Amit Varma]: talking about what happens when a technologically more advanced group

01:53:16.020 --> 01:53:21.420
[Amit Varma]: enters a new territory as would be the case with the area on their horses and

01:53:21.420 --> 01:53:25.580
[Amit Varma]: he writes quote where the population densities are very low as as usual in

01:53:25.580 --> 01:53:30.460
[Amit Varma]: regions occupied by hunter-gatherer bands survivors of a defeated group need

01:53:30.460 --> 01:53:34.260
[Amit Varma]: only move farther away from their enemies where population densities are

01:53:34.260 --> 01:53:39.260
[Amit Varma]: moderate as in regions occupied by food producing tribes no large vacant areas

01:53:39.260 --> 01:53:43.420
[Amit Varma]: remain to which survivors of a defeated band can flee do the victors have no use

01:53:43.420 --> 01:53:47.540
[Amit Varma]: for survivors of a defeated tribe unless to take the women in marriage the

01:53:47.540 --> 01:53:50.940
[Amit Varma]: defeated men are killed and their territory may be occupied by the victors

01:53:50.940 --> 01:53:54.980
[Amit Varma]: alternatively because many such societies have intensive food production

01:53:54.980 --> 01:53:59.140
[Amit Varma]: systems capable of yielding large surpluses the victors can leave the

01:53:59.140 --> 01:54:03.820
[Amit Varma]: defeated in place but deprive them of political autonomy like turning them

01:54:03.820 --> 01:54:07.700
[Amit Varma]: into slaves or assigning them place at the bottom of a caste system that last

01:54:07.700 --> 01:54:11.900
[Amit Varma]: line is your comment after his quote ends and it kind of struck me that that

01:54:11.900 --> 01:54:16.340
[Amit Varma]: this also shows that events that happened thousands of years ago

01:54:16.340 --> 01:54:21.300
[Amit Varma]: literally can lead to a structure that is pervasive to this day that affects

01:54:21.300 --> 01:54:26.860
[Amit Varma]: how we live our lives today number one like Tony in his book for example though

01:54:26.860 --> 01:54:30.380
[Amit Varma]: his timeline is slightly different talks about how essentially all of these

01:54:30.380 --> 01:54:35.260
[Amit Varma]: people who migrated to India from West Asia or the area were basically

01:54:35.260 --> 01:54:39.540
[Amit Varma]: intermingling freely till about you know the common era started and then for the

01:54:39.540 --> 01:54:43.220
[Amit Varma]: last 2,000 years has been strict endogamy because a particular vision of

01:54:43.220 --> 01:54:48.740
[Amit Varma]: society which is the Brahmanical vision of a caste system has kind of won out

01:54:48.740 --> 01:54:52.620
[Amit Varma]: now one this seems pretty incontrovertible that this is kind of how

01:54:52.620 --> 01:54:57.260
[Amit Varma]: it's happened but I'm more keen on the role that language plays in this because

01:54:57.260 --> 01:55:02.580
[Amit Varma]: in language almost seems to play a role in perpetuating these for example

01:55:02.580 --> 01:55:06.020
[Amit Varma]: Sanskrit was denied to women at one point women weren't allowed to learn it

01:55:06.020 --> 01:55:10.900
[Amit Varma]: it was something that was there for the Brahmans you know and and they would

01:55:10.900 --> 01:55:15.340
[Amit Varma]: learn the Vedas by heart and so on and so forth and equally in modern day times

01:55:15.340 --> 01:55:19.780
[Amit Varma]: where we've been invaded at different times by different people and in modern

01:55:19.780 --> 01:55:24.100
[Amit Varma]: day times it seems that English has now become that marker of class which also

01:55:24.100 --> 01:55:27.780
[Amit Varma]: you have a wonderful chapter on where you speak about that and in fact it's

01:55:27.780 --> 01:55:32.020
[Amit Varma]: it's something I bemoan because English being you know in our postcolonial times

01:55:32.020 --> 01:55:35.940
[Amit Varma]: English has become a marker of class and it's almost become a signaling device

01:55:35.940 --> 01:55:40.340
[Amit Varma]: for people to show their sophistication by speaking in fancy English which means

01:55:40.340 --> 01:55:45.500
[Amit Varma]: that a lot of the language that we use contains you know these old archaic

01:55:45.500 --> 01:55:49.540
[Amit Varma]: British pomposities which the British themselves have discarded but we will

01:55:49.540 --> 01:55:54.380
[Amit Varma]: still kind of use language like that like instead of saying stop we'll use a

01:55:54.380 --> 01:55:59.300
[Amit Varma]: phrase like put an end to you know and so on which is disrespectful of whoever's

01:55:59.300 --> 01:56:02.980
[Amit Varma]: reading you or listening to you if you use that kind of language I was shocked

01:56:02.980 --> 01:56:07.420
[Amit Varma]: once to discover on YouTube that there are actually these really popular videos

01:56:07.420 --> 01:56:11.020
[Amit Varma]: supposedly teaching better English to Indians and what they are really saying

01:56:11.020 --> 01:56:16.060
[Amit Varma]: is don't use simple words always use a more complex word so instead of say use

01:56:16.060 --> 01:56:20.220
[Amit Varma]: the word articulate which is exactly the opposite of the advice I'd give where

01:56:20.220 --> 01:56:25.060
[Amit Varma]: the language becomes a signaling device where the language becomes a marker of

01:56:25.060 --> 01:56:31.060
[Amit Varma]: class a marker of social status and so on so how does this affect everything

01:56:31.060 --> 01:56:35.900
[Amit Varma]: that is happening in sort of a subterranean sense where languages are

01:56:35.900 --> 01:56:39.940
[Amit Varma]: changing even Sanskrit is getting retroflex and all of that from the

01:56:39.940 --> 01:56:43.820
[Amit Varma]: language of the conquered people as it were and in later times under the

01:56:43.820 --> 01:56:47.260
[Amit Varma]: Mughals you have sort of you know all the kichris that are popping up

01:56:47.260 --> 01:56:52.740
[Amit Varma]: including Hindi slash Urdu how does language play a part in this and what

01:56:52.740 --> 01:56:57.020
[Amit Varma]: are your sort of observations of language and and these sort of social

01:56:57.020 --> 01:57:01.660
[Guest]: structures that are around us I wouldn't say that language does it I would say

01:57:01.660 --> 01:57:07.700
[Guest]: language reflects it because basically this is something that's happened again

01:57:07.700 --> 01:57:13.420
[Guest]: and again in India at the simplest level I could say once upon a time certain

01:57:13.420 --> 01:57:19.660
[Guest]: people spoke Sanskrit and others didn't women didn't once upon a time certain

01:57:19.660 --> 01:57:24.340
[Guest]: people spoke Persian and everyone else spoke other things the word would do

01:57:24.340 --> 01:57:30.140
[Guest]: didn't wasn't used yet it was just basically Hindi and now certain people

01:57:30.140 --> 01:57:38.460
[Guest]: speak English and others are kept away from it it's basically about a society

01:57:38.460 --> 01:57:47.380
[Guest]: that has a tolerance of inequality and a perception that the elite can exist with

01:57:47.380 --> 01:57:53.300
[Guest]: a code that's completely different from what other people speak so it's

01:57:53.300 --> 01:57:58.460
[Guest]: something that's just been continuing so it isn't that Hindi has done it or

01:57:58.460 --> 01:58:08.020
[Guest]: English has done it they merely have been selected to represent a way of

01:58:08.020 --> 01:58:15.580
[Guest]: expressing inequality and hierarchy in fact in the book I even found that to

01:58:15.580 --> 01:58:21.620
[Guest]: this day we have among say families in Punjab and Haryana you could see

01:58:21.620 --> 01:58:28.100
[Guest]: Manmohan Singh you could see that his the minute the teleprompter is in Urdu

01:58:28.100 --> 01:58:34.060
[Guest]: he becomes an orator and the minute he's reading Devanagari he's uncomfortable

01:58:34.060 --> 01:58:38.940
[Guest]: he's just struggling to read the words he didn't grow up with it but his wife

01:58:38.940 --> 01:58:46.260
[Guest]: would have grown up with Gurmukhi or Devanagari and that that part of India

01:58:46.260 --> 01:58:54.740
[Guest]: Haryana Punjab and maybe even parts of UP you'll find that men were brought up

01:58:54.740 --> 01:59:01.180
[Guest]: with proudly saying that I studied Persian I can read Urdu but I just don't

01:59:01.180 --> 01:59:06.340
[Guest]: know this Hindi thing and their wives are very different and you'd even find

01:59:06.340 --> 01:59:11.420
[Guest]: it going further into the families that the men are non-veg the women are veg

01:59:11.420 --> 01:59:20.180
[Guest]: the men like ghazals the women like bhajans this kind of thing is about a

01:59:20.180 --> 01:59:26.140
[Guest]: fragmentation in so many ways that language is not responsible for it

01:59:26.140 --> 01:59:33.860
[Guest]: except it captures it so very well it's so easy to tell who is who using

01:59:33.860 --> 01:59:39.900
[Guest]: language instead of having to show papers and things like that so as long

01:59:39.900 --> 01:59:45.860
[Guest]: as India has this perception that the elites need to be kept apart and

01:59:45.860 --> 01:59:51.740
[Guest]: privileged by having a code that will guarantee that they and only they can

01:59:51.740 --> 01:59:58.660
[Guest]: access the best jobs this kind of thing is going to happen I think it's sad

01:59:58.660 --> 02:00:05.380
[Guest]: because it's going to mean that all the local languages are in danger because

02:00:05.380 --> 02:00:12.460
[Guest]: poor people are not stupid they understand that English is what is going

02:00:12.460 --> 02:00:18.180
[Guest]: to give the goodies to everyone and they're willing to see their languages

02:00:18.180 --> 02:00:23.380
[Guest]: decline or they haven't given it a thought if their kids can have what we

02:00:23.380 --> 02:00:29.220
[Guest]: have I think that's particularly fair thing to think if we had earlier on

02:00:29.220 --> 02:00:38.580
[Guest]: found some other route of maybe very decentralized education up to a certain

02:00:38.580 --> 02:00:44.340
[Guest]: point and so on our languages might have survived better but for that what would

02:00:44.340 --> 02:00:49.380
[Guest]: have happened is our kids would have been mixing with poor kids and that was

02:00:49.380 --> 02:00:53.380
[Guest]: something that the elite didn't want

02:00:53.380 --> 02:01:00.340
[Amit Varma]: so here's my sort of next broader question one of the themes that kind of

02:01:00.340 --> 02:01:06.060
[Amit Varma]: comes through your book is this jostling between languages where some languages

02:01:06.060 --> 02:01:11.260
[Amit Varma]: evolve and then gain prominence and you know one classic example being Hindi

02:01:11.260 --> 02:01:15.380
[Amit Varma]: gaining prominence while other languages like I grew up thinking that for example

02:01:15.380 --> 02:01:19.900
[Amit Varma]: Bhojpuri and Avadhi and whatever are dialects of Hindi and later on you get

02:01:19.900 --> 02:01:23.220
[Amit Varma]: to realize they're not dialects of Hindi they're completely separate languages

02:01:23.220 --> 02:01:27.140
[Amit Varma]: which have you know with their own rich history and literature and all of that

02:01:27.140 --> 02:01:32.580
[Amit Varma]: and somehow one kind of becomes prominent now there is a process which

02:01:32.580 --> 02:01:36.420
[Amit Varma]: you know one can see in your book one can see through history that smaller

02:01:36.420 --> 02:01:41.500
[Amit Varma]: languages gradually die out and get absorbed in bigger languages and this

02:01:41.500 --> 02:01:45.380
[Amit Varma]: can happen in two ways one way of course is it can just happen through either

02:01:45.380 --> 02:01:49.940
[Amit Varma]: through conquest or one social class becoming dominant in a particular place

02:01:49.940 --> 02:01:53.700
[Amit Varma]: like you know after this we'll talk about you know Kerala and the Nambudiri

02:01:53.700 --> 02:01:58.580
[Amit Varma]: Brahmins and how they along with the Nairs kind of they had a lucky victory

02:01:58.580 --> 02:02:03.060
[Amit Varma]: in conquest and after that their language and whatever kind of takes over

02:02:03.060 --> 02:02:07.460
[Amit Varma]: and that that shapes Malayalam so one way can be through that sort of social

02:02:07.460 --> 02:02:11.260
[Amit Varma]: dominance whether by coercion or not but the other way is simply through

02:02:11.260 --> 02:02:15.020
[Amit Varma]: following incentives like today if you're a young kid who's brought up say

02:02:15.020 --> 02:02:19.300
[Amit Varma]: in a family in rural Maharashtra and you're speaking a particular kind of

02:02:19.300 --> 02:02:23.620
[Amit Varma]: rich dialect of Marathi with its own history and like you said like you've

02:02:23.620 --> 02:02:27.340
[Amit Varma]: pointed out Marathi is like a Creole language which has taken from Sanskrit

02:02:27.340 --> 02:02:32.180
[Amit Varma]: from Dravidian from all over it's not just a simple case that it's a you know

02:02:32.180 --> 02:02:36.340
[Amit Varma]: a child of Sanskrit there's much more that has gone into it each of these so

02:02:36.340 --> 02:02:40.180
[Amit Varma]: called dialects will also be so rich but the incentive for this kid in

02:02:40.180 --> 02:02:45.860
[Amit Varma]: Maharashtra is not necessarily to go deeper into his own language but into

02:02:45.860 --> 02:02:49.460
[Amit Varma]: this language he's born into but to number one learn English and number two

02:02:49.460 --> 02:02:52.860
[Amit Varma]: even if he's you know if he's moving to a big city and he's communicating in

02:02:52.860 --> 02:02:57.820
[Amit Varma]: Marathi with fellow Maharashtrians to then learn and adopt the kind of

02:02:57.820 --> 02:03:02.500
[Amit Varma]: standardized Marathi which everybody else speaks which then you know he or

02:03:02.500 --> 02:03:06.820
[Amit Varma]: she will teach to their own children and in this way you have a sort of a

02:03:06.820 --> 02:03:10.860
[Amit Varma]: consolidation happening where bigger languages take over and people move

02:03:10.860 --> 02:03:13.980
[Amit Varma]: from smaller languages to bigger languages and then the smaller languages

02:03:13.980 --> 02:03:18.180
[Amit Varma]: die and part of that is through sort of conquest and coercion and all of that

02:03:18.180 --> 02:03:22.340
[Amit Varma]: which is a problem but part of it is through people may just making rational

02:03:22.340 --> 02:03:26.500
[Amit Varma]: choices and following incentives and saying this is what I got to do to get

02:03:26.500 --> 02:03:31.740
[Amit Varma]: ahead and it's hard to fault those individuals for making those choices so

02:03:31.740 --> 02:03:35.860
[Amit Varma]: you know how do you sort of think about all of this and do you think this

02:03:35.860 --> 02:03:39.860
[Amit Varma]: process is inevitable because I think whatever value judgment we pass on the

02:03:39.860 --> 02:03:43.540
[Amit Varma]: process that hey diversity is good and we need it and so on do you think that

02:03:43.540 --> 02:03:47.220
[Amit Varma]: it is simply inevitable and we can't do anything about it like just to take

02:03:47.220 --> 02:03:52.020
[Amit Varma]: another digression I did an episode with Vikram doctor once on Indian food and

02:03:52.020 --> 02:03:55.460
[Amit Varma]: how rich it is and how so much of it has actually come from outside and he

02:03:55.460 --> 02:03:59.380
[Amit Varma]: pointed out what has happened to Indian bananas which is basically there was

02:03:59.380 --> 02:04:03.700
[Amit Varma]: something called you know we imported a certain kind of banana outside and that

02:04:03.700 --> 02:04:08.140
[Amit Varma]: became popular elsewhere as the Cavendish banana and then that got

02:04:08.140 --> 02:04:12.300
[Amit Varma]: brought back to India and then the Cavendish banana just spread like

02:04:12.300 --> 02:04:16.660
[Amit Varma]: wildfire because economies of scale and all that kicked in and then it kicked

02:04:16.660 --> 02:04:21.980
[Amit Varma]: out a whole bunch of these indigenous bananas which otherwise existed and

02:04:21.980 --> 02:04:26.340
[Amit Varma]: therefore now we have now we have the fact that one stand of bananas which we

02:04:26.340 --> 02:04:30.620
[Amit Varma]: only exported is now killing all the other bananas we have not because it's

02:04:30.620 --> 02:04:34.980
[Amit Varma]: necessarily a better banana as it were if they can be anything such as a better

02:04:34.980 --> 02:04:39.180
[Amit Varma]: banana but simply because you know economies of scale and all those other

02:04:39.180 --> 02:04:43.300
[Amit Varma]: factors have kicked in and you're losing that diversity so in the context of

02:04:43.300 --> 02:04:50.660
[Amit Varma]: language is it inevitable that we lose that diversity see this all is slightly

02:04:50.660 --> 02:04:58.460
[Guest]: again well like the banana one thing I must say I don't like it either but it

02:04:58.460 --> 02:05:05.220
[Guest]: has shelf life so you'll find that when it comes to fruits shelf life becomes a

02:05:05.220 --> 02:05:12.340
[Guest]: important thing when distance between the farm and the final consumer is so

02:05:12.340 --> 02:05:20.980
[Guest]: much so you're talking about this huge size of the economy that now surrounds

02:05:20.980 --> 02:05:27.580
[Guest]: us what makes a language do well you said conquest but that was earlier now

02:05:27.580 --> 02:05:35.420
[Guest]: it's very simple that the language why did why did Hindi survive and older or

02:05:35.420 --> 02:05:43.420
[Guest]: more pedigreed illustrious literary languages like brudge of a tea not do so

02:05:43.420 --> 02:05:50.340
[Guest]: well it's very simple location Hindi came up in Delhi and Delhi was in all

02:05:50.340 --> 02:05:58.140
[Guest]: sorts of ways a capital even from the time of the Sultanate so which variety

02:05:58.140 --> 02:06:05.060
[Guest]: of Marathi is going to prevail the one that is around the Bombay area so cities

02:06:05.060 --> 02:06:10.660
[Guest]: are very very implicated in the choice of which language is going to survive

02:06:10.660 --> 02:06:17.380
[Guest]: and that also has to do with the fact that being a mega economy and we are

02:06:17.380 --> 02:06:25.500
[Guest]: trying more and more to force a kind of convergence because anybody who's left

02:06:25.500 --> 02:06:31.900
[Guest]: out of the communication loop is out of your control so you want more control of

02:06:31.900 --> 02:06:37.260
[Guest]: people you want them to speak the language even if the elite may not want

02:06:37.260 --> 02:06:45.020
[Guest]: the poor to speak English the internet world does so you're suddenly finding

02:06:45.020 --> 02:06:52.100
[Guest]: people pulled in into an ethos that is not because of language but it's

02:06:52.100 --> 02:06:58.740
[Guest]: definitely reflected in language so we are becoming more and more a global

02:06:58.740 --> 02:07:04.020
[Guest]: community and not necessarily in a very great way it's nice that we can speak to

02:07:04.020 --> 02:07:10.700
[Guest]: just about anyone anywhere but I don't think it is people's choice that is

02:07:10.700 --> 02:07:15.660
[Guest]: making them do it if there were any other way I don't think people would put

02:07:15.660 --> 02:07:20.540
[Guest]: their children in English medium schools and have them staring out the window

02:07:20.540 --> 02:07:27.380
[Guest]: yawning dead silent for years in class it's not something that they would

02:07:27.380 --> 02:07:33.820
[Guest]: regard as pleasant experience for the child but they don't have control over

02:07:33.820 --> 02:07:38.500
[Guest]: the way in which the economy is running and the fact that we are getting more

02:07:38.500 --> 02:07:44.580
[Guest]: and more interconnected networked so that is what has this impact now which

02:07:44.580 --> 02:07:49.860
[Guest]: language our language will be chosen which one will be chosen the one that's

02:07:49.860 --> 02:07:55.780
[Guest]: most associated with the large cities so that's the way it goes it's really not

02:07:55.780 --> 02:08:01.180
[Amit Varma]: linguistic actually yeah it's kind of poignant I have a friend who writes in

02:08:01.180 --> 02:08:04.940
[Amit Varma]: Kannada and wants to be a Kannada writer and he feels most comfortable in a

02:08:04.940 --> 02:08:08.780
[Amit Varma]: dialect of Kannada that a lot of Kannada speak speakers won't even recognize

02:08:08.780 --> 02:08:12.980
[Amit Varma]: that very few people speak in and he is like what should I do because if I write

02:08:12.980 --> 02:08:16.020
[Amit Varma]: in that I will naturally have less readers less chance of getting published

02:08:16.020 --> 02:08:19.620
[Amit Varma]: less whatever and I don't know what to say because the heart says that write in

02:08:19.620 --> 02:08:23.940
[Amit Varma]: what you know best but the head says that you know you also want to put food

02:08:23.940 --> 02:08:27.540
[Amit Varma]: in it you want to be read I would just say you know picking off on some phrase

02:08:27.540 --> 02:08:30.460
[Amit Varma]: that you use that even if the elite don't want the poor to learn English I

02:08:30.460 --> 02:08:33.500
[Amit Varma]: don't think that would be the case I think the elites on the contrary would

02:08:33.500 --> 02:08:37.700
[Amit Varma]: want the poor to learn English because it increases their sort of networks like

02:08:37.700 --> 02:08:41.620
[Amit Varma]: in a similar way that Macaulay wanted us to learn English so that they could be

02:08:41.620 --> 02:08:45.820
[Amit Varma]: of course Macaulay's reasons were exploitative and very zero-sum but I

02:08:45.820 --> 02:08:48.980
[Amit Varma]: think you know within India the more people that know English the more the

02:08:48.980 --> 02:08:52.180
[Amit Varma]: markets are more the chances for prosperity because that is what English

02:08:52.180 --> 02:08:58.100
[Guest]: does there's a problem which is if my child is brilliant it really does not

02:08:58.100 --> 02:09:02.980
[Guest]: matter who competes with my child my child will do well but if my child is a

02:09:02.980 --> 02:09:09.940
[Guest]: very ordinary mediocre child I need something that is yes and if you put

02:09:09.940 --> 02:09:15.740
[Guest]: something as a gatekeeper like a language which my child has which is not

02:09:15.740 --> 02:09:25.740
[Guest]: a sign of greater intellect but it can be posed as a important attribute of

02:09:25.740 --> 02:09:33.020
[Guest]: some of or requirement for a job my child will always do better than a brilliant

02:09:33.020 --> 02:09:37.940
[Guest]: child who doesn't have this language doing it's the ultimate reservation

02:09:37.940 --> 02:09:44.900
[Guest]: system of the elite for the kids they have who probably could not compete in a

02:09:44.900 --> 02:09:49.620
[Amit Varma]: fair fight I guess it comes down to whether you have a zero-sum mindset or a

02:09:49.620 --> 02:09:53.700
[Amit Varma]: positive some mindset and a lot of Indians sadly do seem to be stuck in the

02:09:53.700 --> 02:09:58.060
[Amit Varma]: zero-sum mindset but that said I think you know English has become such an

02:09:58.060 --> 02:10:02.660
[Amit Varma]: aspirational language in India that you and and you of course also point out in

02:10:02.660 --> 02:10:07.740
[Amit Varma]: your chapter on English how you know English has become so pervasive that

02:10:07.740 --> 02:10:12.260
[Amit Varma]: even people who think that they speak only in Hindi actually don't that they

02:10:12.260 --> 02:10:15.980
[Amit Varma]: are using a lot of English words and and I would argue that's not necessarily a

02:10:15.980 --> 02:10:19.300
[Amit Varma]: bad thing those English words have just become part of the language it you know

02:10:19.300 --> 02:10:24.300
[Amit Varma]: it's an Indian language but do you bemoan it because of the danger that some

02:10:24.300 --> 02:10:27.460
[Amit Varma]: languages may die because of this because the English ization of

02:10:27.460 --> 02:10:32.020
[Amit Varma]: everything or you know because on the whole language is evolving in this way

02:10:32.020 --> 02:10:37.580
[Amit Varma]: is just the way history goes and it's not necessarily something bad see again

02:10:37.580 --> 02:10:42.980
[Guest]: it's not about language it's about political choices economic choices if we

02:10:42.980 --> 02:10:50.540
[Guest]: live in a world that's more controlled by the tech world of Silicon Valley or

02:10:50.540 --> 02:10:57.700
[Guest]: global enterprises you're going to find a wish for streamlining into a single

02:10:57.700 --> 02:11:04.580
[Guest]: language so I don't sit and worry about languages dying because people will

02:11:04.580 --> 02:11:11.940
[Guest]: survive but I think that the entire idea of having a single language for such an

02:11:11.940 --> 02:11:20.780
[Guest]: enormous community as the global community is flawed and I'm I'm not very

02:11:20.780 --> 02:11:26.860
[Guest]: convinced that what we're doing in terms of the way the world is moving is the

02:11:26.860 --> 02:11:33.660
[Guest]: right one or it's even in our control anymore so so these are very political

02:11:33.660 --> 02:11:39.140
[Guest]: things I'm saying or political or socio-economic but they're not linguistic

02:11:39.140 --> 02:11:46.180
[Guest]: language follows from this so to preserve languages you can't preserve a

02:11:46.180 --> 02:11:51.620
[Guest]: language that you don't really use as long as you don't get your medical

02:11:51.620 --> 02:11:57.660
[Guest]: reports in Hindi you're preserving it for what to have it as a pretty thing

02:11:57.660 --> 02:12:04.580
[Guest]: like a tiger in a zoo to say we haven't killed the last tiger whereas I don't

02:12:04.580 --> 02:12:10.260
[Guest]: like the word preserve I think that anything is in if you have a fair

02:12:10.260 --> 02:12:15.900
[Guest]: situation things will thrive on their own the point is we don't have a fair

02:12:15.900 --> 02:12:22.900
[Guest]: situation so that's why these languages are all under threat and as to where

02:12:22.900 --> 02:12:30.220
[Guest]: this is going to go it's in a sense it's another mass extinction like what we're

02:12:30.220 --> 02:12:35.820
[Guest]: seeing that the only animals left are going to be livestock and pets you know

02:12:35.820 --> 02:12:42.100
[Guest]: and the only languages left are the ones that are convenient to the world of tech

02:12:42.100 --> 02:12:48.100
[Guest]: and big business so ultimately all these things that we've been talking about all

02:12:48.100 --> 02:12:54.100
[Guest]: my answers to you in the last half an hour or so have taken it away from

02:12:54.100 --> 02:12:59.580
[Guest]: linguistics and into socio-economics and politics because that's where the real

02:12:59.580 --> 02:13:04.220
[Amit Varma]: fight is yeah that's a great point I mean what you're really pointing out is

02:13:04.220 --> 02:13:08.780
[Amit Varma]: that listen you know if there is if society is ill then language is just a

02:13:08.780 --> 02:13:12.860
[Amit Varma]: symptom it is not the cause it you can look at it and say that okay languages

02:13:12.860 --> 02:13:16.380
[Amit Varma]: follow in this way or one language becomes dominant because of something

02:13:16.380 --> 02:13:19.500
[Amit Varma]: else that's wrong there's nothing inherent in the language which of course

02:13:19.500 --> 02:13:23.940
[Amit Varma]: is a case if I might pose a slight counterpoint to the not even a

02:13:23.940 --> 02:13:28.100
[Amit Varma]: counterpoint I agree with you entirely but another way of sort of looking at

02:13:28.100 --> 02:13:33.620
[Amit Varma]: this is that while everybody in India for example would want to know English

02:13:33.620 --> 02:13:38.020
[Amit Varma]: for functional reasons and and more and more people also are talking about you

02:13:38.020 --> 02:13:42.060
[Amit Varma]: know learning Mandarin or at one point learning Spanish would be a thing

02:13:42.060 --> 02:13:45.380
[Amit Varma]: elsewhere in the world and all those are for functional reasons because you you

02:13:45.380 --> 02:13:48.980
[Amit Varma]: you want to be part of that wider economy and be able to communicate but

02:13:48.980 --> 02:13:54.220
[Amit Varma]: I'm not so sure that it is always at the expense of languages dying out like all

02:13:54.220 --> 02:13:58.500
[Amit Varma]: our cinemas our regional cinemas are flourishing I used to be a big fan of

02:13:58.500 --> 02:14:02.860
[Amit Varma]: tik-tok I even taught a brief course on tik-tok in Indian society and there it

02:14:02.860 --> 02:14:05.860
[Amit Varma]: wasn't that people were expressing themselves in English or anything you

02:14:05.860 --> 02:14:08.740
[Amit Varma]: could make out from their clothes and whatever that there was a lot of

02:14:08.740 --> 02:14:12.540
[Amit Varma]: aspiration there but they were expressing themselves in local languages

02:14:12.540 --> 02:14:15.300
[Amit Varma]: where sometimes even if I didn't understand the language I could still

02:14:15.300 --> 02:14:19.700
[Amit Varma]: make out what's going on and I would find it hilarious and in a sense I would

02:14:19.700 --> 02:14:23.900
[Amit Varma]: say that the more diversity you have in terms of entertainment and platforms and

02:14:23.900 --> 02:14:27.780
[Amit Varma]: being able to express yourself the more chance the more diversity of expression

02:14:27.780 --> 02:14:31.500
[Amit Varma]: you will have and therefore the chance that languages may survive like I think

02:14:31.500 --> 02:14:35.180
[Amit Varma]: in your book if I remember correctly you also point out you're surprised at

02:14:35.180 --> 02:14:39.740
[Amit Varma]: bhojpuri which was once not a major language has actually now become a big

02:14:39.740 --> 02:14:43.460
[Amit Varma]: language in its own right is that correct do I remember correctly up to a

02:14:43.460 --> 02:14:49.540
[Guest]: point in fact that's a very good example because bhojpuri has managed to command

02:14:49.540 --> 02:14:55.260
[Guest]: politics and entertainment but that's only half the battle the big battle for

02:14:55.260 --> 02:15:01.460
[Guest]: a language is does it command technology does it command the banking sector does

02:15:01.460 --> 02:15:08.860
[Guest]: it command government that's easy of course but technology and science are

02:15:08.860 --> 02:15:14.520
[Guest]: the things that really tell you if there's no scientific discourse in the

02:15:14.520 --> 02:15:20.100
[Guest]: language it's a body blow to it like you look at places like the Philippines and

02:15:20.100 --> 02:15:25.980
[Guest]: South Africa there's entertainment in local languages but they are visibly

02:15:25.980 --> 02:15:31.460
[Guest]: traumatized because it's only reached the level of entertainment the the

02:15:31.460 --> 02:15:38.340
[Guest]: really tough thing is where whether futuristic stuff like science and

02:15:38.340 --> 02:15:42.960
[Guest]: technology are done in the language you can do any amount of bureaucracy you

02:15:42.960 --> 02:15:50.500
[Guest]: could pass a law and say all government memos in whatever language but science

02:15:50.500 --> 02:15:56.820
[Guest]: and technology once they're not China is way ahead they it's in Chinese Japan

02:15:56.820 --> 02:16:03.700
[Guest]: it's in Japanese Iran it's in Farsi Turkey it's in Turkish all the

02:16:03.700 --> 02:16:10.740
[Guest]: Scandinavian countries but in India that's this is an important point even

02:16:10.740 --> 02:16:17.220
[Guest]: something like doing mathematics any Indian educated in English adds a column

02:16:17.220 --> 02:16:24.500
[Guest]: of figures in English nobody else in the world can do that they a sweet will add

02:16:24.500 --> 02:16:32.340
[Guest]: in Swedish and tell you the answer in English so this is in a way there are

02:16:32.340 --> 02:16:37.060
[Guest]: features of a language which give it a little bit of a lease on life

02:16:37.060 --> 02:16:46.540
[Guest]: entertainment literature even is one but without those top layers which reach

02:16:46.540 --> 02:16:55.700
[Guest]: into the future you are you know riding for bad times and that's true of every

02:16:55.700 --> 02:17:01.260
[Guest]: Indian language that's that's my worry we're not seeing it because just to see

02:17:01.260 --> 02:17:07.500
[Guest]: so much literature so much stuff in print so much entertainment pop songs

02:17:07.500 --> 02:17:15.740
[Guest]: it's a small part of the journey yeah no very wise points and thinking

02:17:15.740 --> 02:17:18.700
[Amit Varma]: allowed like if I look at the country like China for example it strikes me

02:17:18.700 --> 02:17:23.260
[Amit Varma]: that it this can both be a feature and a bug that on the one hand yes they have

02:17:23.260 --> 02:17:27.260
[Amit Varma]: kind of managed to get where they are without relying on English to the point

02:17:27.260 --> 02:17:30.260
[Amit Varma]: that now people in the West are saying hey we got to learn Mandarin and we got

02:17:30.260 --> 02:17:34.380
[Amit Varma]: to figure this out in China's a big bar but at the same time they've been very

02:17:34.380 --> 02:17:39.980
[Amit Varma]: insular and this also kind of comes at a cost that insularity is obviously again

02:17:39.980 --> 02:17:43.260
[Amit Varma]: not a good thing you want to open yourself up to influences from

02:17:43.260 --> 02:17:47.060
[Amit Varma]: everywhere the danger in opening or yourself up to influences from

02:17:47.060 --> 02:17:50.420
[Amit Varma]: everywhere is that you can get run over by them especially when you know

02:17:50.420 --> 02:17:54.180
[Amit Varma]: economies of scale come in as they do in the case of the Cavendish banana which

02:17:54.180 --> 02:17:57.260
[Amit Varma]: like you said there are rational reasons for people to prefer the Cavendish

02:17:57.260 --> 02:18:01.220
[Amit Varma]: bananas to other bananas that they last longer but nevertheless what happens is

02:18:01.220 --> 02:18:06.140
[Amit Varma]: that diversity suffers and those other bananas go out of play and with India I

02:18:06.140 --> 02:18:10.500
[Amit Varma]: think it's kind of a unique situation because English was a dominant the

02:18:10.500 --> 02:18:14.780
[Amit Varma]: language for a long time under colonialism that the hangover of that

02:18:14.780 --> 02:18:19.100
[Amit Varma]: sort of remained and other languages were kind of you know driven into

02:18:19.100 --> 02:18:23.240
[Amit Varma]: different directions you know I mean how do you even reverse that now you you

02:18:23.240 --> 02:18:27.420
[Amit Varma]: can't for example tell people that no your children must only be schooled in

02:18:27.420 --> 02:18:30.260
[Amit Varma]: your local languages you can't do that because you'll be denying them

02:18:30.260 --> 02:18:33.940
[Amit Varma]: opportunities it would again come down to the same thing of the elites creating

02:18:33.940 --> 02:18:38.840
[Amit Varma]: a new kind of sort of apartheid as it were through language so I think in

02:18:38.840 --> 02:18:41.820
[Amit Varma]: modern times is good that everyone learns English but I completely get your

02:18:41.820 --> 02:18:46.060
[Amit Varma]: sort of worry about what happens to the other languages I mean I'm optimistic

02:18:46.060 --> 02:18:50.020
[Amit Varma]: enough to hope that there'll be enough ways of people expressing themselves and

02:18:50.020 --> 02:18:52.580
[Amit Varma]: for all of these to stay alive but you're shaking your head and you know I

02:18:52.580 --> 02:18:58.460
[Guest]: don't see it I believe that it's a myth that bilingualism is a sustainable thing

02:18:58.460 --> 02:19:05.140
[Guest]: in the old days when in India we had a very stable social structure and you

02:19:05.140 --> 02:19:10.460
[Guest]: could know three or four languages in parallel we got the illusion that that's

02:19:10.460 --> 02:19:15.180
[Guest]: something that Indians were very good at but the modern world is a little

02:19:15.180 --> 02:19:21.500
[Guest]: different when people learn two languages or learn another language in

02:19:21.500 --> 02:19:30.020
[Guest]: India English or the main regional language it's not quite the same as it

02:19:30.020 --> 02:19:34.940
[Guest]: used to be before because there's an arrow of direction with it it isn't that

02:19:34.940 --> 02:19:39.220
[Guest]: we plan to live our lives and our children's lives and their children's

02:19:39.220 --> 02:19:45.460
[Guest]: lives in three languages we are in transit to a new one language we

02:19:45.460 --> 02:19:49.500
[Guest]: already have children coming into the schools in India who only know English

02:19:49.500 --> 02:19:57.220
[Guest]: and who might pick up a local language as a subject never read a single piece

02:19:57.220 --> 02:20:04.500
[Guest]: of literature in it so can it be reversed is it good if you have ever

02:20:04.500 --> 02:20:11.580
[Guest]: been in a class where 25% of the kids don't really know English you find that

02:20:11.580 --> 02:20:18.140
[Guest]: there's a terrible illusion that just by spouting gibberish at them they will

02:20:18.140 --> 02:20:23.100
[Guest]: learn it they will not so it's a very inefficient way to teach English in fact

02:20:23.100 --> 02:20:28.140
[Guest]: if what you wanted to do was teach English the best way to teach English is

02:20:28.140 --> 02:20:34.620
[Guest]: to not teach it in its medium but to allow children to learn about the world

02:20:34.620 --> 02:20:43.580
[Guest]: and separately learn English now where that's going to take us is probably not

02:20:43.580 --> 02:20:50.380
[Guest]: even a terribly different place as long as the world is centralizing more and

02:20:50.380 --> 02:20:56.740
[Guest]: more language will do the same thing is it a good thing well for that you just

02:20:56.740 --> 02:21:00.380
[Guest]: have to answer the question is it a good thing that we have no more wild animals

02:21:00.380 --> 02:21:05.900
[Guest]: and it's only pets and livestock is it a good thing that we have less and less of

02:21:05.900 --> 02:21:12.500
[Guest]: wild plants but only crops and gardens and lawns lawn the most absolutely

02:21:12.500 --> 02:21:21.420
[Guest]: useless thing so these are choices that ultimately are not about language so in

02:21:21.420 --> 02:21:29.740
[Guest]: my book I do say that when languages die it's like a canary taken into a mine

02:21:29.740 --> 02:21:36.540
[Guest]: that it will die long before you can even feel that the air has changed so

02:21:36.540 --> 02:21:42.540
[Guest]: it's another one of those marks of a mass extinction I don't have a strong

02:21:42.540 --> 02:21:48.580
[Guest]: position on it and what we should do except to say that the word mass

02:21:48.580 --> 02:21:54.060
[Guest]: extinction is a scary word and which it should give us a moment of pause to

02:21:54.060 --> 02:21:57.660
[Guest]: think about where we going and the answer of course is not going to be

02:21:57.660 --> 02:22:02.180
[Amit Varma]: linguistic I agree with all of that except that I think I'm less

02:22:02.180 --> 02:22:07.220
[Amit Varma]: pessimistic but that could just be from my own sort of availability heuristic

02:22:07.220 --> 02:22:10.620
[Amit Varma]: where I can look around me and you know I can speak multiple languages so can

02:22:10.620 --> 02:22:14.140
[Amit Varma]: the people around me but it would be dangerous to assume that that is always

02:22:14.140 --> 02:22:19.500
[Amit Varma]: necessarily going to be the case so we'll see how that pans out now one

02:22:19.500 --> 02:22:23.180
[Amit Varma]: chapter that I really found fascinating in your book was about the Sanskrit

02:22:23.180 --> 02:22:27.260
[Amit Varma]: words in Malayalam because my assumption was that hey listen the South Indian

02:22:27.260 --> 02:22:31.140
[Amit Varma]: languages are completely separate they won't let you know Sanskrit in but then

02:22:31.140 --> 02:22:35.300
[Amit Varma]: you point out how deeply Malayalam is sanskritized and in fact Malayalam is a

02:22:35.300 --> 02:22:38.900
[Amit Varma]: beautiful language in that sense though I don't know it but because there's so

02:22:38.900 --> 02:22:43.720
[Amit Varma]: many influences from so many places from from Arabic from all the you know the

02:22:43.720 --> 02:22:49.700
[Amit Varma]: different kinds of traders Jews Arabs and Syrian Christians who kind of landed

02:22:49.700 --> 02:22:52.820
[Amit Varma]: up there all of whom shaped the language in their own way but the

02:22:52.820 --> 02:22:57.240
[Amit Varma]: sanskritization is really interesting because it really begins with what the

02:22:57.240 --> 02:23:01.220
[Amit Varma]: happenstance of the way that a particular military battle works out

02:23:01.220 --> 02:23:07.500
[Amit Varma]: like your quote K Sugandhan in a book that he wrote in Malayalam writing about

02:23:07.500 --> 02:23:11.620
[Amit Varma]: how quote at just about this time in Kerala Buddhists were defeated by the

02:23:11.620 --> 02:23:15.540
[Amit Varma]: Brahmin community in the Nair forces fighting on their side Buddhist and Jain

02:23:15.540 --> 02:23:19.500
[Amit Varma]: groups who did not accept the dominance of the Brahmins saw a sharp decline in

02:23:19.500 --> 02:23:25.780
[Amit Varma]: status and were assigned to Ezowa and Thiyarkas. I'm so apologies to

02:23:25.780 --> 02:23:29.820
[Amit Varma]: everyone who might be offended by this Ezowa and Thiyarkas within a resurgent

02:23:29.820 --> 02:23:33.180
[Amit Varma]: caste system while groups like the Nair's who had supported the Brahmins

02:23:33.180 --> 02:23:38.020
[Amit Varma]: remained secure stop quote and later on your right quote sanskritized Malayalam

02:23:38.020 --> 02:23:41.540
[Amit Varma]: appeared at exactly the same time that Brahminical Hinduism was being

02:23:41.540 --> 02:23:45.520
[Amit Varma]: re-established in Kerala and when the Namudiri Brahmin community had every

02:23:45.520 --> 02:23:51.500
[Amit Varma]: reason to celebrate its good fortune. So tell me a little bit about what happened

02:23:51.500 --> 02:23:56.940
[Amit Varma]: here like was it a case of sort of a creolization of a new Malayalam coming

02:23:56.940 --> 02:24:02.460
[Amit Varma]: up or was it just sort of very superficial series of loan words being

02:24:02.460 --> 02:24:07.620
[Amit Varma]: taken from Sanskrit into Malayalam what exactly was a process by which a new

02:24:07.620 --> 02:24:11.540
[Amit Varma]: Malayalam which was distinct from the old Malayalam came about and what was a

02:24:11.540 --> 02:24:18.300
[Guest]: nature of this distinction? Okay I'll do it by comparing another language in a

02:24:18.300 --> 02:24:24.100
[Guest]: southern part of India which is Urdu in the Deccan. In both of these languages

02:24:24.100 --> 02:24:32.180
[Guest]: Deccani Urdu and modern Malayalam with Sanskrit words the people who first

02:24:32.180 --> 02:24:39.940
[Guest]: started it were people who knew Sanskrit or Persian. So for them to it was not a

02:24:39.940 --> 02:24:46.620
[Guest]: question of adding in Sanskrit. They knew the language they were getting away from

02:24:46.620 --> 02:24:53.980
[Guest]: Sanskrit by putting Sanskrit in a matrix of the local language or putting Persian

02:24:53.980 --> 02:25:00.180
[Guest]: words in Deccani in the matrix of the local language. So it's not an addition

02:25:00.180 --> 02:25:08.460
[Guest]: it's a subtraction. It taking out all the verbs yeah also notice that in Malayalam

02:25:08.460 --> 02:25:16.060
[Guest]: and in Rehta Urdu only nouns. So that whenever they stuck for a noun they went

02:25:16.060 --> 02:25:21.620
[Guest]: to Persian or they went to Sanskrit. Sanskrit itself in the north you we tell

02:25:21.620 --> 02:25:26.380
[Guest]: ourselves that the we have Sanskrit words they're actually prakrit words but

02:25:26.380 --> 02:25:33.540
[Guest]: in Kerala it was actually Sanskrit where read that summer Sanskrit. The point is

02:25:33.540 --> 02:25:40.340
[Guest]: that people who always wrote in Sanskrit or always wrote in Persian took the

02:25:40.340 --> 02:25:45.220
[Guest]: decision not to do it but they did an English kind of thing. They kept adding

02:25:45.220 --> 02:25:51.260
[Guest]: in all these words when they were stuck. So it was not realization it was

02:25:51.260 --> 02:26:00.140
[Guest]: obviously something else but I didn't have a word for it but here I see two

02:26:00.140 --> 02:26:08.820
[Guest]: things, two parts of India where nouns have come into something that is local

02:26:08.820 --> 02:26:13.540
[Guest]: and the nouns have come from somewhere else. No verbs, no endings,

02:26:13.540 --> 02:26:19.740
[Guest]: nothing, no grammar just the nouns. So Malayalam is still very much a South

02:26:19.740 --> 02:26:27.140
[Guest]: Indian language but it has a bunch of nouns which come from Sanskrit. So what

02:26:27.140 --> 02:26:33.380
[Guest]: to call that I haven't given it a name. Somebody should give it a name but it's

02:26:33.380 --> 02:26:39.420
[Amit Varma]: not a prakrit. It's so fascinating how sort of nouns are the easiest thing to

02:26:39.420 --> 02:26:44.100
[Amit Varma]: kind of transplant and the structure remains what it is or you know might

02:26:44.100 --> 02:26:50.100
[Guest]: adopt slightly but nouns are just easiest and then you like you if I saw

02:26:50.100 --> 02:26:54.820
[Guest]: you in a kurta pajama or I saw you in what you're wearing now there would be a

02:26:54.820 --> 02:27:01.060
[Guest]: stark difference in how you would look but it would be the same you whereas if

02:27:01.060 --> 02:27:08.740
[Guest]: there had been actual body transplants or you had a child who was half from

02:27:08.740 --> 02:27:14.140
[Guest]: completely different community there you would see big differences but this is

02:27:14.140 --> 02:27:20.380
[Amit Varma]: just clothing. If my child was a tiramisu bear for example, let's move on.

02:27:20.380 --> 02:27:23.680
[Amit Varma]: In fact I'm not going to talk about any more of the chapters individually

02:27:23.680 --> 02:27:26.500
[Amit Varma]: because we've already spoken for two and a half hours and I just want to ask

02:27:26.500 --> 02:27:31.340
[Amit Varma]: broader questions now but implore all of my listeners to go and read the full

02:27:31.340 --> 02:27:35.540
[Amit Varma]: book. I mean the chapters on the Indo-Aryan languages and then on Hindi and

02:27:35.540 --> 02:27:40.380
[Amit Varma]: Urdu were absolutely fascinating. So I'm going to now kind of move on to my next

02:27:40.380 --> 02:27:44.700
[Amit Varma]: broad question but before that you mentioned Khusro earlier, Amir Khusro and

02:27:44.700 --> 02:27:48.580
[Amit Varma]: Amir Khusro is of course this fascinating character who was born in

02:27:48.580 --> 02:27:53.220
[Amit Varma]: the year 1253 and he seems to sort of be a metaphor for what is happening in the

02:27:53.220 --> 02:27:57.860
[Amit Varma]: Indian languages itself. As you point out, quote, as a young boy Khusro is said to

02:27:57.860 --> 02:28:02.140
[Amit Varma]: have learned Turki, the language was not yet called Uzbek, Arabic, Persian and

02:28:02.140 --> 02:28:05.900
[Amit Varma]: Sanskrit and he also picked up various dialects spoken in the Delhi region such

02:28:05.900 --> 02:28:10.020
[Amit Varma]: as Awadhi, Brajbhasha, Bhojpuri and the new language of the urban gentry known

02:28:10.020 --> 02:28:15.580
[Amit Varma]: as Khariboli or Dehlavi or simply as Hindi. The name Urdu would only come with

02:28:15.580 --> 02:28:20.580
[Amit Varma]: the poet Mushafi by the late 18th century. Stop quote. And then you quote

02:28:20.580 --> 02:28:25.380
[Amit Varma]: this beautiful lines by him where he writes about his peer Hazrat Nizamuddin

02:28:25.380 --> 02:28:35.980
[Amit Varma]: Auliya where he says, and very resonant words and easy for me to

02:28:35.980 --> 02:28:41.620
[Amit Varma]: understand even now in this current time. But when I later read Ghalib and as you

02:28:41.620 --> 02:28:44.700
[Amit Varma]: point out most of Ghalib's work is in Persian and only some of it is in Urdu

02:28:44.700 --> 02:28:50.820
[Amit Varma]: but even the what Ghalib writes in Urdu is very heavily Persianized. Very cryptic.

02:28:50.820 --> 02:28:56.740
[Amit Varma]: Very Persianized and you've pointed out about how during this time his mentor

02:28:56.740 --> 02:29:00.780
[Amit Varma]: initially was Bahadur Shah Zafar who himself was like a pensioner kept

02:29:00.780 --> 02:29:04.780
[Amit Varma]: captive in the Red Fort by the British. So Ghalib did not want to piss the

02:29:04.780 --> 02:29:08.900
[Amit Varma]: British off and therefore he kept it cryptic. More Persian went into his

02:29:08.900 --> 02:29:14.820
[Amit Varma]: poetry as it were and at this point in the 19th century over a period of a few

02:29:14.820 --> 02:29:20.060
[Amit Varma]: decades what happens is that Urdu gets more and more Persianized and Hindi gets

02:29:20.060 --> 02:29:24.740
[Amit Varma]: more and more Sanskritized because at the same time there is this political

02:29:24.740 --> 02:29:28.620
[Amit Varma]: movement happening where you know Alok Rai has written a book called Hindi

02:29:28.620 --> 02:29:33.060
[Amit Varma]: nationalism on this where the whole movement is that Hindi is our pure

02:29:33.060 --> 02:29:37.220
[Amit Varma]: language and we must strip foreign elements from it which is not of course

02:29:37.220 --> 02:29:41.980
[Amit Varma]: the case. It was never a pure form. It just evolved as a combination of all

02:29:41.980 --> 02:29:46.060
[Amit Varma]: these various things. So Hindi is Sanskritized in the way that nobody

02:29:46.060 --> 02:29:52.900
[Amit Varma]: actually speaks like that kind of Shudh Hindi is not spoken anywhere per se and

02:29:52.900 --> 02:29:57.300
[Amit Varma]: equally Urdu gets Persianized for a variety of different reasons like that

02:29:57.300 --> 02:30:00.500
[Amit Varma]: and they diverge even though to begin with they are the same language

02:30:00.500 --> 02:30:04.380
[Amit Varma]: fundamentally and they diverge. In fact you've pointed out how Munshi Premchand

02:30:04.380 --> 02:30:08.340
[Amit Varma]: son Amrit Rai wrote a book about criticizing Ghalib and what he did with

02:30:08.340 --> 02:30:12.880
[Amit Varma]: this beautiful language that he just Persianized it heavily which seems at

02:30:12.880 --> 02:30:16.220
[Amit Varma]: some level to me to be the equivalent of if someone was to you

02:30:16.220 --> 02:30:20.460
[Amit Varma]: know take regular spoken English and just put in a lot of big Latinate words

02:30:20.460 --> 02:30:25.060
[Amit Varma]: and it would be like I think a similar kind of effect would happen and some

02:30:25.060 --> 02:30:28.500
[Amit Varma]: people will of course do that to signal that you know I know this language so

02:30:28.500 --> 02:30:33.300
[Amit Varma]: well and all of that but a similar kind of thing would happen. This just shows

02:30:33.300 --> 02:30:39.660
[Amit Varma]: how politics plays such a huge part in language and independent India has also

02:30:39.660 --> 02:30:43.980
[Amit Varma]: of course grappled with that and in that sense perhaps you know the fact that we

02:30:43.980 --> 02:30:47.820
[Amit Varma]: have English at least is a blessing because otherwise you know people might

02:30:47.820 --> 02:30:51.340
[Amit Varma]: have tried to impose Hindi on the southern states which would not have

02:30:51.340 --> 02:30:56.620
[Guest]: gone down well with good reason. Not the kind of Hindi that they were going to

02:30:56.620 --> 02:31:03.420
[Guest]: impose, definitely not. Notice that the Hindi that came up in the Shudh Hindi was

02:31:03.420 --> 02:31:09.380
[Guest]: like in Malayalam, Tatsama Hindi. It was never the case in the past. The kind of

02:31:09.380 --> 02:31:15.740
[Guest]: words that came were from Prakrit, never from Sanskrit. So to just barge in there

02:31:15.740 --> 02:31:23.220
[Guest]: and put Sanskrit words was a failure to notice how language had formed in the

02:31:23.220 --> 02:31:27.700
[Guest]: past and it wasn't done by Indians initially. It was done by the British

02:31:27.700 --> 02:31:35.260
[Guest]: because they were very unhappy with well the importance of the language spoken by

02:31:35.260 --> 02:31:39.100
[Guest]: their predecessors so they were trying to break these languages and they

02:31:39.100 --> 02:31:45.540
[Guest]: managed to do it. However, when you talk of Ghalib, let's remember he didn't only

02:31:45.540 --> 02:31:52.500
[Guest]: write Ghazals and poetry. He also wrote, I remember going in fact into the Ghalib

02:31:52.500 --> 02:32:00.380
[Guest]: Institute, they have a library, to get out his collected letters and which were

02:32:00.380 --> 02:32:06.340
[Guest]: collected actually 50 years after he died and they give a bit of an overview

02:32:06.340 --> 02:32:12.780
[Guest]: of how he felt in those days because they were not published as such and you

02:32:12.780 --> 02:32:17.540
[Guest]: would understand most of the Urdu. It's nothing like his poetry. His

02:32:17.540 --> 02:32:26.140
[Guest]: poetry is difficult not because of the language per se. He's being very devious

02:32:26.140 --> 02:32:32.580
[Guest]: in how he frames his thoughts. It's a puzzle. He's writing like Zen koans for

02:32:32.580 --> 02:32:39.700
[Guest]: you and if you, in fact, if you live with a Ghazal in your head for years, its

02:32:39.700 --> 02:32:43.260
[Guest]: meaning is going to change depending upon the things that are happening in

02:32:43.260 --> 02:32:50.020
[Guest]: your own life. So, he did have another Urdu which was much more normal, much

02:32:50.020 --> 02:32:55.620
[Guest]: more down-to-earth. But that gets lost because that's not what many

02:32:55.620 --> 02:33:04.700
[Guest]: people look for in him. But yes, it's very hard to imagine that the British were

02:33:04.700 --> 02:33:12.300
[Guest]: successfully splitting the old Mughal elite from the modern Hindu citizens of

02:33:12.300 --> 02:33:19.340
[Guest]: their empire without it having a repercussion on the language. So, they

02:33:19.340 --> 02:33:25.340
[Guest]: managed to split the language and people began to think that this strange thing

02:33:25.340 --> 02:33:30.740
[Guest]: written in Persian script is not the same thing as what we have that has

02:33:30.740 --> 02:33:39.580
[Guest]: borrowed a whole lot of new Sanskrit words. So, again, politics and somebody

02:33:39.580 --> 02:33:47.220
[Guest]: intervening and the famous term divided rule. They did that. Language is just one

02:33:47.220 --> 02:33:52.900
[Amit Varma]: area. No, and you've actually reproduced in your book one of Ghalib's letters. So,

02:33:52.900 --> 02:33:57.660
[Amit Varma]: which reads so differently like someone is asking him about the destruction of

02:33:57.660 --> 02:34:02.740
[Amit Varma]: Delhi and he begins with the words, Bhai, kya pooshte ho, kya likho? And then he goes on in

02:34:02.740 --> 02:34:07.020
[Amit Varma]: language that anyone sitting today can really understand and relate to and we

02:34:07.020 --> 02:34:10.900
[Amit Varma]: might use some of those, some of the same language ourselves while his, you know,

02:34:10.900 --> 02:34:14.940
[Amit Varma]: Ghazals and all are quite different which is fascinating. So, this is very

02:34:14.940 --> 02:34:19.740
[Amit Varma]: interesting how the British, you know, create this sharp political divide and

02:34:19.740 --> 02:34:25.140
[Amit Varma]: so on. So, when we look at modern-day politics also, for example, especially in

02:34:25.140 --> 02:34:29.580
[Amit Varma]: these trying times, you know, and this is not just a question purely about

02:34:29.580 --> 02:34:34.420
[Amit Varma]: language but as someone who's observed society over a while, who has seen larger

02:34:34.420 --> 02:34:39.140
[Amit Varma]: political trends play out, in fact, through the centuries. So, in that

02:34:39.140 --> 02:34:43.020
[Amit Varma]: capacity, like it is very easy, for example, to sit in the present moment and

02:34:43.020 --> 02:34:48.860
[Amit Varma]: be despondent about the current trends that are going on but equally someone

02:34:48.860 --> 02:34:52.620
[Amit Varma]: may just sit back and say, no, listen, we've been here before, it's okay, we'll

02:34:52.620 --> 02:34:56.500
[Amit Varma]: get through this. There are things within society that are stronger than these

02:34:56.500 --> 02:35:02.340
[Amit Varma]: currents that are there right now in our politics. So, how does one think about it?

02:35:02.340 --> 02:35:05.460
[Amit Varma]: Like earlier, you were a little more pessimistic than I was about the

02:35:05.460 --> 02:35:09.540
[Amit Varma]: survival of some of these languages and what was being done to them because

02:35:09.540 --> 02:35:12.660
[Amit Varma]: being an expert in languages when you write the kind of book that you have

02:35:12.660 --> 02:35:16.980
[Amit Varma]: done also means that you are also writing about politics and society and

02:35:16.980 --> 02:35:20.820
[Amit Varma]: all of that. So, I'm going to take a step outside language for a moment and

02:35:20.820 --> 02:35:25.980
[Amit Varma]: just ask you on what is your feeling about all of this as someone who is from

02:35:25.980 --> 02:35:30.180
[Amit Varma]: Delhi as, you know, as you tell people who you've been here for more than 40

02:35:30.180 --> 02:35:34.700
[Amit Varma]: years but equally you have a wider view of the whole world but you also have a

02:35:34.700 --> 02:35:39.980
[Amit Varma]: deeper view of India itself because of all your incredible insights in this, as

02:35:39.980 --> 02:35:42.780
[Amit Varma]: your incredible insights in this book indicate about both the language and the

02:35:42.780 --> 02:35:47.020
[Amit Varma]: society. What is your sense of what is going on and what role does language

02:35:47.020 --> 02:35:50.460
[Amit Varma]: play on it? Like, as an aside, like sometimes when I see our Prime Minister's

02:35:50.460 --> 02:35:55.420
[Amit Varma]: speeches on TV, it seems to me that he's speaking a certain shuddh kind of Hindi,

02:35:55.420 --> 02:35:59.340
[Amit Varma]: not to the same extent as someone like Vajpayee did a couple of decades ago but

02:35:59.340 --> 02:36:03.660
[Amit Varma]: he's speaking a certain shuddh kind of Hindi and not an everyday lingo kind of

02:36:03.660 --> 02:36:07.860
[Amit Varma]: language where, you know, he would famously say mitro instead of dosto as

02:36:07.860 --> 02:36:11.940
[Amit Varma]: people would say in common speech and, you know, and I don't understand how that

02:36:11.940 --> 02:36:16.380
[Amit Varma]: goes down so well among so many people who don't speak the language but anyway

02:36:16.380 --> 02:36:22.020
[Amit Varma]: that's a digression but in general, you know, with that wider understanding of

02:36:22.020 --> 02:36:25.300
[Amit Varma]: history and with all the frames that you've gathered, when you look at this

02:36:25.300 --> 02:36:32.180
[Guest]: present time, how do you feel? See, since I told you earlier with language, what

02:36:32.180 --> 02:36:37.580
[Guest]: worries me is that it's all, all the tributaries are coming to one single

02:36:37.580 --> 02:36:42.620
[Guest]: river. In the past, there were many tributaries going to many rivers and we

02:36:42.620 --> 02:36:48.220
[Guest]: said we've seen this before, we can go ahead but when it's all coming into one,

02:36:48.220 --> 02:36:56.100
[Guest]: we're seeing something a little bit scary and as to where this goes in the

02:36:56.100 --> 02:37:05.180
[Guest]: future, I think we're beginning to see pushback. I don't regard the whole COVID

02:37:05.180 --> 02:37:14.260
[Guest]: experience as a one-off. It's just the first thing that's being done to shake

02:37:14.260 --> 02:37:21.020
[Guest]: our entire notion of where we are going and they're going to be others. There's

02:37:21.020 --> 02:37:27.980
[Guest]: no way there will not be pushback against this rollercoaster we're on,

02:37:27.980 --> 02:37:35.220
[Guest]: taking us towards a more and more centralized world with a few billionaires

02:37:35.220 --> 02:37:41.140
[Guest]: and others completely on the outside. I'm not even talking about just India, this

02:37:41.140 --> 02:37:47.900
[Guest]: is the world. We are in for a lot of surprises. If you think of what Zoom

02:37:47.900 --> 02:37:54.300
[Guest]: classes have done to education, you suddenly realize that I'm not very sure

02:37:54.300 --> 02:38:00.980
[Guest]: how we're stepping out of the world we've constructed in the last two years. So a

02:38:00.980 --> 02:38:06.940
[Guest]: lot of things are going to, people are going to be ripe for thinking afresh

02:38:06.940 --> 02:38:11.940
[Guest]: about a lot of things. Is it nice to travel all the way across Delhi to

02:38:11.940 --> 02:38:18.140
[Guest]: school? Maybe some local things are a better way, maybe it's nice to be able to

02:38:18.140 --> 02:38:25.180
[Guest]: be going places in your daily life where you can walk or cycle, where maybe it's

02:38:25.180 --> 02:38:31.860
[Guest]: nice for children to be able to be close to school and to go without their

02:38:31.860 --> 02:38:37.980
[Guest]: parents' intervention. In fact, the more centralized the world has been, the more

02:38:37.980 --> 02:38:42.540
[Guest]: children have needed their parents to completely shepherd them through it. So

02:38:42.540 --> 02:38:48.580
[Guest]: what I'm trying to say is we've reached a point where the surprises are going to

02:38:48.580 --> 02:38:54.460
[Guest]: start coming and we are not really primed for them. We're going to have to

02:38:54.460 --> 02:39:03.020
[Guest]: react in some way. So on the political front, what's happening now is similar to

02:39:03.020 --> 02:39:07.780
[Guest]: what's happening in many parts of the world and what's going to happen next, I

02:39:07.780 --> 02:39:12.620
[Guest]: am thinking it's going to be surprises because it cannot continue. We cannot

02:39:12.620 --> 02:39:21.140
[Guest]: have more and more inequality, more and more strife among communities. Something

02:39:21.140 --> 02:39:26.980
[Guest]: has got to give and it's going to give, as Steve Gold would have said, in a

02:39:26.980 --> 02:39:31.580
[Guest]: punctuated sort of a way. Sudden things are going to happen and we're going to

02:39:31.580 --> 02:39:38.980
[Guest]: face shocks and how language will respond to that is to what extent these

02:39:38.980 --> 02:39:45.820
[Guest]: shocks force us to fragment into more manageable zones. Remember the 12th

02:39:45.820 --> 02:39:54.700
[Guest]: century in India and Europe, both places were about breaking up over large

02:39:54.700 --> 02:40:03.180
[Guest]: expanses of power. Latin, Prakrit, Sanskrit, all fragmented into smaller

02:40:03.180 --> 02:40:08.980
[Guest]: manageable units. It happened then. So I don't know what will happen in the

02:40:08.980 --> 02:40:17.860
[Guest]: future except that this is one of the possibilities. But we are, as I said in

02:40:17.860 --> 02:40:23.700
[Amit Varma]: the book, racing towards a stop sign. That's fascinating, the notion

02:40:23.700 --> 02:40:26.580
[Amit Varma]: that we might be heading towards a kind of punctuated equilibria where

02:40:26.580 --> 02:40:30.580
[Amit Varma]: everything just sort of changes. And I would hope it changes. I mean, there is a

02:40:30.580 --> 02:40:34.060
[Amit Varma]: possibility that it changes for the better. You know, looking at our

02:40:34.060 --> 02:40:38.220
[Amit Varma]: politics, I tend to be more pessimistic than optimistic. But when you think of

02:40:38.220 --> 02:40:41.660
[Amit Varma]: language, I think the biggest pushback is actually coming from our artists and

02:40:41.660 --> 02:40:46.380
[Amit Varma]: writers. I think of Hussain Haidri's poem Hindustani Musalma, Varun Grover Kaagaz

02:40:46.380 --> 02:40:50.700
[Amit Varma]: Nahi Dikhayenge, where they are using language in a beautiful, relatable way to

02:40:50.700 --> 02:40:54.300
[Amit Varma]: express dissent. You see the amazing work our cartoonists are doing, in fact,

02:40:54.300 --> 02:40:58.300
[Amit Varma]: where, you know, language is not even such a big part of that. So I think there

02:40:58.300 --> 02:41:03.020
[Amit Varma]: is hope in art and there is hope in common people. But you know, but who

02:41:03.020 --> 02:41:07.580
[Amit Varma]: knows? Let's see. I'll end by sort of asking you a question I often ask all my

02:41:07.580 --> 02:41:12.540
[Amit Varma]: guests. It's almost become a meme of the show that people want to know what books

02:41:12.540 --> 02:41:15.980
[Amit Varma]: to read about particular subjects. So when my guest recommends books, they'll

02:41:15.980 --> 02:41:19.780
[Amit Varma]: often go out and buy those, post pictures of those on Twitter. All of that happens,

02:41:19.780 --> 02:41:23.780
[Amit Varma]: which is something I absolutely love and encourage because we all should really

02:41:23.780 --> 02:41:27.260
[Amit Varma]: read more. So what I'm going to ask you to do, and I don't want to restrict you

02:41:27.260 --> 02:41:31.060
[Amit Varma]: to books about language, which is the obvious thing, because your book is not

02:41:31.060 --> 02:41:35.340
[Amit Varma]: just about language. It is about so much else. I mean, it's I mean, it's one of

02:41:35.340 --> 02:41:38.860
[Amit Varma]: those books which, you know, I was telling you before the show that I often

02:41:38.860 --> 02:41:43.140
[Amit Varma]: say that to understand India's history, two books that you must read by authors

02:41:43.140 --> 02:41:47.820
[Amit Varma]: I've done episodes with are, you know, Early Indians by Tony Joseph and India

02:41:47.820 --> 02:41:51.580
[Amit Varma]: moving by Chinmay Tumbe on the history of migration. And I absolutely include

02:41:51.580 --> 02:41:55.020
[Amit Varma]: your book now as a third prong of that. And I'm sure there are many more prongs

02:41:55.020 --> 02:41:59.140
[Amit Varma]: and much for us to discover. But I felt that in so many different ways, which I

02:41:59.140 --> 02:42:03.380
[Amit Varma]: couldn't even touch the surface of during this episode, your book opened my

02:42:03.380 --> 02:42:07.420
[Amit Varma]: eyes to so many things and gave me so much to think about. So on similar lines,

02:42:07.420 --> 02:42:10.860
[Amit Varma]: if somebody reads your book and says that, hey, this was great, I want to read

02:42:10.860 --> 02:42:13.980
[Amit Varma]: more books like this. What would you recommend? Like, are there any books

02:42:13.980 --> 02:42:17.860
[Amit Varma]: which change the way you look at the world? What are the sort of books that

02:42:17.860 --> 02:42:21.780
[Amit Varma]: you feel so enthusiastic about that you want to throw it at people and say, read

02:42:21.780 --> 02:42:29.420
[Guest]: it now? Okay, they will not be in linguistics. But there is a style of

02:42:29.420 --> 02:42:36.340
[Guest]: writing, which I think all these people, Tony Joseph probably, I would say, me, I

02:42:36.340 --> 02:42:44.380
[Guest]: hope. It's called science narratives, where you're posing very complex scientific

02:42:44.380 --> 02:42:51.700
[Guest]: issues, but writing it in somewhat accessible style, which involves a

02:42:51.700 --> 02:42:56.460
[Guest]: certain amount of walking around the corridors of your hospital. You see it

02:42:56.460 --> 02:43:01.860
[Guest]: with somebody like Siddharth Mukherjee. I particularly liked his first book, The

02:43:01.860 --> 02:43:09.780
[Guest]: Emperor of All Maladies. That's a style. But for stuff that gives me a lot of

02:43:09.780 --> 02:43:15.180
[Guest]: food for thought, there's a writer I like, and his name is David Quammen. And he

02:43:15.180 --> 02:43:23.140
[Guest]: writes on issues to do with biology. And the earlier books, of course, the

02:43:23.140 --> 02:43:27.060
[Guest]: first one that I would say I really love is The Song of the Dodo. It's talking

02:43:27.060 --> 02:43:33.940
[Guest]: about extinctions and comparing extinctions in that situation to the

02:43:33.940 --> 02:43:39.660
[Guest]: extinctions of language that I work on. And then, of course, his latest

02:43:39.660 --> 02:43:45.140
[Guest]: book, unless he's written after that, is called The Tangled Tree. So you're

02:43:45.140 --> 02:43:56.820
[Guest]: looking at how genes are influenced by invading viruses, bacteria, etc. And in a

02:43:56.820 --> 02:44:03.820
[Guest]: way, it's not just a style of the science narrative that I'm hoping I am trying, I

02:44:03.820 --> 02:44:13.460
[Guest]: am trying my best to get to, but the issues are very similar. Extinctions are

02:44:13.460 --> 02:44:19.020
[Guest]: something we worry about. Predators are things that we worry about. Predator

02:44:19.020 --> 02:44:26.500
[Guest]: languages. So, and he's written a number of books, so you can go through that and

02:44:26.500 --> 02:44:35.340
[Guest]: read about quite a number of things that impact language or are parallel to the

02:44:35.340 --> 02:44:42.460
[Guest]: problems that we have. So like, just as I went to Stephen Jay Gould to read about

02:44:42.460 --> 02:44:49.220
[Guest]: what would be a natural life cycle for a language, I go to somebody like Quammen

02:44:49.220 --> 02:44:55.740
[Guest]: to see how this is posed in a style that makes a decent book, that somebody can

02:44:55.740 --> 02:45:02.020
[Guest]: actually read extremely difficult things in and still not be overwhelmed by it.

02:45:02.020 --> 02:45:07.580
[Guest]: You see the kind of style that I'm thinking of. I remember reading books by

02:45:07.580 --> 02:45:13.620
[Guest]: Ravela Thapar and Irfan Habib, and there was this lovely feeling at the end of

02:45:13.620 --> 02:45:20.860
[Guest]: the book of just going through the notes just as a standalone thing because I

02:45:20.860 --> 02:45:26.420
[Guest]: felt the book was not enough. I wanted more, and there was more. There were the

02:45:26.420 --> 02:45:31.860
[Guest]: notes. So that was another thing that I think in my own book I tried to get

02:45:31.860 --> 02:45:36.180
[Guest]: because these were also people who were looking at the same kinds of issues in

02:45:36.180 --> 02:45:45.980
[Guest]: terms of history. So I'm looking at style and patterns, content. These are the kind

02:45:45.980 --> 02:45:52.100
[Guest]: of people I would want to recommend. Yeah, and that's such a lovely thought, the

02:45:52.100 --> 02:45:55.140
[Amit Varma]: thought of, you know, looking at the end notes of a book or looking at the

02:45:55.140 --> 02:46:00.380
[Amit Varma]: bibliography and entering rabbit holes, which I keep, you know, doing a lot of

02:46:00.380 --> 02:46:03.420
[Amit Varma]: the time. And you mentioned David Quammen. I mean, the only book I've read

02:46:03.420 --> 02:46:07.220
[Amit Varma]: of his is Spillover, which actually came out a few years ago, but it's about

02:46:07.220 --> 02:46:11.500
[Amit Varma]: zoonotic viruses. So the moment sort of COVID struck, I started reading up on it

02:46:11.500 --> 02:46:16.900
[Amit Varma]: and that's a lovely book as well. So, Peggy, what can I say? Thank you so much.

02:46:16.900 --> 02:46:22.180
[Guest]: I know that you're traveling right now. You're in Mexico right now on the way to

02:46:22.180 --> 02:46:27.380
[Amit Varma]: San Francisco. Yeah, so it's so kind of you to, you know, share your time and

